 860     def style(self) -> "Styler":
 861         """
 862         Returns a Styler object.
 863 
 864         Contains methods for building a styled HTML representation of the DataFrame.
 865 
 866         See Also
 867         --------
 868         io.formats.style.Styler : Helps style a DataFrame or Series according to the
 869             data with HTML and CSS.
 870         """
 871         from pandas.io.formats.style import Styler
 872 
 873         return Styler(self)
 874 
 875     _shared_docs[
 876         "items"
 877     ] = r"""
 878         Iterate over (column name, Series) pairs.
 879 
 880         Iterates over the DataFrame columns, returning a tuple with
 881         the column name and the content as a Series.
 882 
 883         Yields
 884         ------
 885         label : object
 886             The column names for the DataFrame being iterated over.
 887         content : Series
 888             The column entries belonging to each label, as a Series.
 889 
 890         See Also
 891         --------
 892         DataFrame.iterrows : Iterate over DataFrame rows as
 893             (index, Series) pairs.
 894         DataFrame.itertuples : Iterate over DataFrame rows as namedtuples
 895             of the values.
 896 
 897         Examples
 898         --------
 899         >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'species': ['bear', 'bear', 'marsupial'],
 900         ...                   'population': [1864, 22000, 80000]},
 901         ...                   index=['panda', 'polar', 'koala'])
 902         >>> df
 903                 species   population
 904         panda   bear      1864
 905         polar   bear      22000
 906         koala   marsupial 80000
 907         >>> for label, content in df.items():
 908         ...     print(f'label: {label}')
 909         ...     print(f'content: {content}', sep='\n')
 910         ...
 911         label: species
 912         content:
 913         panda         bear
 914         polar         bear
 915         koala    marsupial
 916         Name: species, dtype: object
 917         label: population
 918         content:
 919         panda     1864
 920         polar    22000
 921         koala    80000
 922         Name: population, dtype: int64
 923         """
 924 
 925     @Appender(_shared_docs["items"])
 926     def items(self) -> Iterable[Tuple[Label, Series]]:
 927         if self.columns.is_unique and hasattr(self, "_item_cache"):
 928             for k in self.columns:
 929                 yield k, self._get_item_cache(k)
 930         else:
 931             for i, k in enumerate(self.columns):
 932                 yield k, self._ixs(i, axis=1)
 933 
 934     @Appender(_shared_docs["items"])
 935     def iteritems(self) -> Iterable[Tuple[Label, Series]]:
 936         yield from self.items()
 937 
 938     def iterrows(self) -> Iterable[Tuple[Label, Series]]:
 939         """
 940         Iterate over DataFrame rows as (index, Series) pairs.
 941 
 942         Yields
 943         ------
 944         index : label or tuple of label
 945             The index of the row. A tuple for a `MultiIndex`.
 946         data : Series
 947             The data of the row as a Series.
 948 
 949         it : generator
 950             A generator that iterates over the rows of the frame.
 951 
 952         See Also
 953         --------
 954         DataFrame.itertuples : Iterate over DataFrame rows as namedtuples of the values.
 955         DataFrame.items : Iterate over (column name, Series) pairs.
 956 
 957         Notes
 958         -----
 959         1. Because ``iterrows`` returns a Series for each row,
 960            it does **not** preserve dtypes across the rows (dtypes are
 961            preserved across columns for DataFrames). For example,
 962 
 963            >>> df = pd.DataFrame([[1, 1.5]], columns=['int', 'float'])
 964            >>> row = next(df.iterrows())[1]
 965            >>> row
 966            int      1.0
 967            float    1.5
 968            Name: 0, dtype: float64
 969            >>> print(row['int'].dtype)
 970            float64
 971            >>> print(df['int'].dtype)
 972            int64
 973 
 974            To preserve dtypes while iterating over the rows, it is better
 975            to use :meth:`itertuples` which returns namedtuples of the values
 976            and which is generally faster than ``iterrows``.
 977 
 978         2. You should **never modify** something you are iterating over.
 979            This is not guaranteed to work in all cases. Depending on the
 980            data types, the iterator returns a copy and not a view, and writing
 981            to it will have no effect.
 982         """
 983         columns = self.columns
 984         klass = self._constructor_sliced
 985         for k, v in zip(self.index, self.values):
 986             s = klass(v, index=columns, name=k)
 987             yield k, s
 988 
 989     def itertuples(self, index=True, name="Pandas"):
 990         """
 991         Iterate over DataFrame rows as namedtuples.
 992 
 993         Parameters
 994         ----------
 995         index : bool, default True
 996             If True, return the index as the first element of the tuple.
 997         name : str or None, default "Pandas"
 998             The name of the returned namedtuples or None to return regular
 999             tuples.
1000 
1001         Returns
1002         -------
1003         iterator
1004             An object to iterate over namedtuples for each row in the
1005             DataFrame with the first field possibly being the index and
1006             following fields being the column values.
1007 
1008         See Also
1009         --------
1010         DataFrame.iterrows : Iterate over DataFrame rows as (index, Series)
1011             pairs.
1012         DataFrame.items : Iterate over (column name, Series) pairs.
1013 
1014         Notes
1015         -----
1016         The column names will be renamed to positional names if they are
1017         invalid Python identifiers, repeated, or start with an underscore.
1018         On python versions < 3.7 regular tuples are returned for DataFrames
1019         with a large number of columns (>254).
1020 
1021         Examples
1022         --------
1023         >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'num_legs': [4, 2], 'num_wings': [0, 2]},
1024         ...                   index=['dog', 'hawk'])
1025         >>> df
1026               num_legs  num_wings
1027         dog          4          0
1028         hawk         2          2
1029         >>> for row in df.itertuples():
1030         ...     print(row)
1031         ...
1032         Pandas(Index='dog', num_legs=4, num_wings=0)
1033         Pandas(Index='hawk', num_legs=2, num_wings=2)
1034 
1035         By setting the `index` parameter to False we can remove the index
1036         as the first element of the tuple:
1037 
1038         >>> for row in df.itertuples(index=False):
1039         ...     print(row)
1040         ...
1041         Pandas(num_legs=4, num_wings=0)
1042         Pandas(num_legs=2, num_wings=2)
1043 
1044         With the `name` parameter set we set a custom name for the yielded
1045         namedtuples:
1046 
1047         >>> for row in df.itertuples(name='Animal'):
1048         ...     print(row)
1049         ...
1050         Animal(Index='dog', num_legs=4, num_wings=0)
1051         Animal(Index='hawk', num_legs=2, num_wings=2)
1052         """
1053         arrays = []
1054         fields = list(self.columns)
1055         if index:
1056             arrays.append(self.index)
1057             fields.insert(0, "Index")
1058 
1059         # use integer indexing because of possible duplicate column names
1060         arrays.extend(self.iloc[:, k] for k in range(len(self.columns)))
1061 
1062         # Python versions before 3.7 support at most 255 arguments to constructors
1063         can_return_named_tuples = PY37 or len(self.columns) + index < 255
1064         if name is not None and can_return_named_tuples:
1065             itertuple = collections.namedtuple(name, fields, rename=True)
1066             return map(itertuple._make, zip(*arrays))
1067 
1068         # fallback to regular tuples
1069         return zip(*arrays)
1070 
1071     def __len__(self) -> int:
1072         """
1073         Returns length of info axis, but here we use the index.
1074         """
1075         return len(self.index)
1076 
1077     def dot(self, other):
1078         """
1079         Compute the matrix multiplication between the DataFrame and other.
1080 
1081         This method computes the matrix product between the DataFrame and the
1082         values of an other Series, DataFrame or a numpy array.
1083 
1084         It can also be called using ``self @ other`` in Python >= 3.5.
1085 
1086         Parameters
1087         ----------
1088         other : Series, DataFrame or array-like
1089             The other object to compute the matrix product with.
1090 
1091         Returns
1092         -------
1093         Series or DataFrame
1094             If other is a Series, return the matrix product between self and
1095             other as a Series. If other is a DataFrame or a numpy.array, return
1096             the matrix product of self and other in a DataFrame of a np.array.
1097 
1098         See Also
1099         --------
1100         Series.dot: Similar method for Series.
1101 
1102         Notes
1103         -----
1104         The dimensions of DataFrame and other must be compatible in order to
1105         compute the matrix multiplication. In addition, the column names of
1106         DataFrame and the index of other must contain the same values, as they
1107         will be aligned prior to the multiplication.
1108 
1109         The dot method for Series computes the inner product, instead of the
1110         matrix product here.
1111 
1112         Examples
1113         --------
1114         Here we multiply a DataFrame with a Series.
1115 
1116         >>> df = pd.DataFrame([[0, 1, -2, -1], [1, 1, 1, 1]])
1117         >>> s = pd.Series([1, 1, 2, 1])
1118         >>> df.dot(s)
1119         0    -4
1120         1     5
1121         dtype: int64
1122 
1123         Here we multiply a DataFrame with another DataFrame.
1124 
1125         >>> other = pd.DataFrame([[0, 1], [1, 2], [-1, -1], [2, 0]])
1126         >>> df.dot(other)
1127             0   1
1128         0   1   4
1129         1   2   2
1130 
1131         Note that the dot method give the same result as @
1132 
1133         >>> df @ other
1134             0   1
1135         0   1   4
1136         1   2   2
1137 
1138         The dot method works also if other is an np.array.
1139 
1140         >>> arr = np.array([[0, 1], [1, 2], [-1, -1], [2, 0]])
1141         >>> df.dot(arr)
1142             0   1
1143         0   1   4
1144         1   2   2
1145 
1146         Note how shuffling of the objects does not change the result.
1147 
1148         >>> s2 = s.reindex([1, 0, 2, 3])
1149         >>> df.dot(s2)
1150         0    -4
1151         1     5
1152         dtype: int64
1153         """
1154         if isinstance(other, (Series, DataFrame)):
1155             common = self.columns.union(other.index)
1156             if len(common) > len(self.columns) or len(common) > len(other.index):
1157                 raise ValueError("matrices are not aligned")
1158 
1159             left = self.reindex(columns=common, copy=False)
1160             right = other.reindex(index=common, copy=False)
1161             lvals = left.values
1162             rvals = right._values
1163         else:
1164             left = self
1165             lvals = self.values
1166             rvals = np.asarray(other)
1167             if lvals.shape[1] != rvals.shape[0]:
1168                 raise ValueError(
1169                     f"Dot product shape mismatch, {lvals.shape} vs {rvals.shape}"
1170                 )
1171 
1172         if isinstance(other, DataFrame):
1173             return self._constructor(
1174                 np.dot(lvals, rvals), index=left.index, columns=other.columns
1175             )
1176         elif isinstance(other, Series):
1177             return self._constructor_sliced(np.dot(lvals, rvals), index=left.index)
1178         elif isinstance(rvals, (np.ndarray, Index)):
1179             result = np.dot(lvals, rvals)
1180             if result.ndim == 2:
1181                 return self._constructor(result, index=left.index)
1182             else:
1183                 return self._constructor_sliced(result, index=left.index)
1184         else:  # pragma: no cover
1185             raise TypeError(f"unsupported type: {type(other)}")
1186 
1187     def __matmul__(self, other):
1188         """
1189         Matrix multiplication using binary `@` operator in Python>=3.5.
1190         """
1191         return self.dot(other)
1192 
1193     def __rmatmul__(self, other):
1194         """
1195         Matrix multiplication using binary `@` operator in Python>=3.5.
1196         """
1197         return self.T.dot(np.transpose(other)).T
1198 
1199     # ----------------------------------------------------------------------
1200     # IO methods (to / from other formats)
1201 
1202     @classmethod
1203     def from_dict(cls, data, orient="columns", dtype=None, columns=None) -> "DataFrame":
1204         """
1205         Construct DataFrame from dict of array-like or dicts.
1206 
1207         Creates DataFrame object from dictionary by columns or by index
1208         allowing dtype specification.
1209 
1210         Parameters
1211         ----------
1212         data : dict
1213             Of the form {field : array-like} or {field : dict}.
1214         orient : {'columns', 'index'}, default 'columns'
1215             The "orientation" of the data. If the keys of the passed dict
1216             should be the columns of the resulting DataFrame, pass 'columns'
1217             (default). Otherwise if the keys should be rows, pass 'index'.
1218         dtype : dtype, default None
1219             Data type to force, otherwise infer.
1220         columns : list, default None
1221             Column labels to use when ``orient='index'``. Raises a ValueError
1222             if used with ``orient='columns'``.
1223 
1224             .. versionadded:: 0.23.0
1225 
1226         Returns
1227         -------
1228         DataFrame
1229 
1230         See Also
1231         --------
1232         DataFrame.from_records : DataFrame from structured ndarray, sequence
1233             of tuples or dicts, or DataFrame.
1234         DataFrame : DataFrame object creation using constructor.
1235 
1236         Examples
1237         --------
1238         By default the keys of the dict become the DataFrame columns:
1239 
1240         >>> data = {'col_1': [3, 2, 1, 0], 'col_2': ['a', 'b', 'c', 'd']}
1241         >>> pd.DataFrame.from_dict(data)
1242            col_1 col_2
1243         0      3     a
1244         1      2     b
1245         2      1     c
1246         3      0     d
1247 
1248         Specify ``orient='index'`` to create the DataFrame using dictionary
1249         keys as rows:
1250 
1251         >>> data = {'row_1': [3, 2, 1, 0], 'row_2': ['a', 'b', 'c', 'd']}
1252         >>> pd.DataFrame.from_dict(data, orient='index')
1253                0  1  2  3
1254         row_1  3  2  1  0
1255         row_2  a  b  c  d
1256 
1257         When using the 'index' orientation, the column names can be
1258         specified manually:
1259 
1260         >>> pd.DataFrame.from_dict(data, orient='index',
1261         ...                        columns=['A', 'B', 'C', 'D'])
1262                A  B  C  D
1263         row_1  3  2  1  0
1264         row_2  a  b  c  d
1265         """
1266         index = None
1267         orient = orient.lower()
1268         if orient == "index":
1269             if len(data) > 0:
1270                 # TODO speed up Series case
1271                 if isinstance(list(data.values())[0], (Series, dict)):
1272                     data = _from_nested_dict(data)
1273                 else:
1274                     data, index = list(data.values()), list(data.keys())
1275         elif orient == "columns":
1276             if columns is not None:
1277                 raise ValueError("cannot use columns parameter with orient='columns'")
1278         else:  # pragma: no cover
1279             raise ValueError("only recognize index or columns for orient")
1280 
1281         return cls(data, index=index, columns=columns, dtype=dtype)
1282 
1283     def to_numpy(
1284         self, dtype=None, copy: bool = False, na_value=lib.no_default
1285     ) -> np.ndarray:
1286         """
1287         Convert the DataFrame to a NumPy array.
1288 
1289         .. versionadded:: 0.24.0
1290 
1291         By default, the dtype of the returned array will be the common NumPy
1292         dtype of all types in the DataFrame. For example, if the dtypes are
1293         ``float16`` and ``float32``, the results dtype will be ``float32``.
1294         This may require copying data and coercing values, which may be
1295         expensive.
1296 
1297         Parameters
1298         ----------
1299         dtype : str or numpy.dtype, optional
1300             The dtype to pass to :meth:`numpy.asarray`.
1301         copy : bool, default False
1302             Whether to ensure that the returned value is not a view on
1303             another array. Note that ``copy=False`` does not *ensure* that
1304             ``to_numpy()`` is no-copy. Rather, ``copy=True`` ensure that
1305             a copy is made, even if not strictly necessary.
1306         na_value : Any, optional
1307             The value to use for missing values. The default value depends
1308             on `dtype` and the dtypes of the DataFrame columns.
1309 
1310             .. versionadded:: 1.1.0
1311 
1312         Returns
1313         -------
1314         numpy.ndarray
1315 
1316         See Also
1317         --------
1318         Series.to_numpy : Similar method for Series.
1319 
1320         Examples
1321         --------
1322         >>> pd.DataFrame({"A": [1, 2], "B": [3, 4]}).to_numpy()
1323         array([[1, 3],
1324                [2, 4]])
1325 
1326         With heterogeneous data, the lowest common type will have to
1327         be used.
1328 
1329         >>> df = pd.DataFrame({"A": [1, 2], "B": [3.0, 4.5]})
1330         >>> df.to_numpy()
1331         array([[1. , 3. ],
1332                [2. , 4.5]])
1333 
1334         For a mix of numeric and non-numeric types, the output array will
1335         have object dtype.
1336 
1337         >>> df['C'] = pd.date_range('2000', periods=2)
1338         >>> df.to_numpy()
1339         array([[1, 3.0, Timestamp('2000-01-01 00:00:00')],
1340                [2, 4.5, Timestamp('2000-01-02 00:00:00')]], dtype=object)
1341         """
1342         result = self._mgr.as_array(
1343             transpose=self._AXIS_REVERSED, dtype=dtype, copy=copy, na_value=na_value
1344         )
1345 
1346         return result
1347 
1348     def to_dict(self, orient="dict", into=dict):
1349         """
1350         Convert the DataFrame to a dictionary.
1351 
1352         The type of the key-value pairs can be customized with the parameters
1353         (see below).
1354 
1355         Parameters
1356         ----------
1357         orient : str {'dict', 'list', 'series', 'split', 'records', 'index'}
1358             Determines the type of the values of the dictionary.
1359 
1360             - 'dict' (default) : dict like {column -> {index -> value}}
1361             - 'list' : dict like {column -> [values]}
1362             - 'series' : dict like {column -> Series(values)}
1363             - 'split' : dict like
1364               {'index' -> [index], 'columns' -> [columns], 'data' -> [values]}
1365             - 'records' : list like
1366               [{column -> value}, ... , {column -> value}]
1367             - 'index' : dict like {index -> {column -> value}}
1368 
1369             Abbreviations are allowed. `s` indicates `series` and `sp`
1370             indicates `split`.
1371 
1372         into : class, default dict
1373             The collections.abc.Mapping subclass used for all Mappings
1374             in the return value.  Can be the actual class or an empty
1375             instance of the mapping type you want.  If you want a
1376             collections.defaultdict, you must pass it initialized.
1377 
1378         Returns
1379         -------
1380         dict, list or collections.abc.Mapping
1381             Return a collections.abc.Mapping object representing the DataFrame.
1382             The resulting transformation depends on the `orient` parameter.
1383 
1384         See Also
1385         --------
1386         DataFrame.from_dict: Create a DataFrame from a dictionary.
1387         DataFrame.to_json: Convert a DataFrame to JSON format.
1388 
1389         Examples
1390         --------
1391         >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'col1': [1, 2],
1392         ...                    'col2': [0.5, 0.75]},
1393         ...                   index=['row1', 'row2'])
1394         >>> df
1395               col1  col2
1396         row1     1  0.50
1397         row2     2  0.75
1398         >>> df.to_dict()
1399         {'col1': {'row1': 1, 'row2': 2}, 'col2': {'row1': 0.5, 'row2': 0.75}}
1400 
1401         You can specify the return orientation.
1402 
1403         >>> df.to_dict('series')
1404         {'col1': row1    1
1405                  row2    2
1406         Name: col1, dtype: int64,
1407         'col2': row1    0.50
1408                 row2    0.75
1409         Name: col2, dtype: float64}
1410 
1411         >>> df.to_dict('split')
1412         {'index': ['row1', 'row2'], 'columns': ['col1', 'col2'],
1413          'data': [[1, 0.5], [2, 0.75]]}
1414 
1415         >>> df.to_dict('records')
1416         [{'col1': 1, 'col2': 0.5}, {'col1': 2, 'col2': 0.75}]
1417 
1418         >>> df.to_dict('index')
1419         {'row1': {'col1': 1, 'col2': 0.5}, 'row2': {'col1': 2, 'col2': 0.75}}
1420 
1421         You can also specify the mapping type.
1422 
1423         >>> from collections import OrderedDict, defaultdict
1424         >>> df.to_dict(into=OrderedDict)
1425         OrderedDict([('col1', OrderedDict([('row1', 1), ('row2', 2)])),
1426                      ('col2', OrderedDict([('row1', 0.5), ('row2', 0.75)]))])
1427 
1428         If you want a `defaultdict`, you need to initialize it:
1429 
1430         >>> dd = defaultdict(list)
1431         >>> df.to_dict('records', into=dd)
1432         [defaultdict(<class 'list'>, {'col1': 1, 'col2': 0.5}),
1433          defaultdict(<class 'list'>, {'col1': 2, 'col2': 0.75})]
1434         """
1435         if not self.columns.is_unique:
1436             warnings.warn(
1437                 "DataFrame columns are not unique, some columns will be omitted.",
1438                 UserWarning,
1439                 stacklevel=2,
1440             )
1441         # GH16122
1442         into_c = com.standardize_mapping(into)
1443 
1444         orient = orient.lower()
1445         # GH32515
1446         if orient.startswith(("d", "l", "s", "r", "i")) and orient not in {
1447             "dict",
1448             "list",
1449             "series",
1450             "split",
1451             "records",
1452             "index",
1453         }:
1454             warnings.warn(
1455                 "Using short name for 'orient' is deprecated. Only the "
1456                 "options: ('dict', list, 'series', 'split', 'records', 'index') "
1457                 "will be used in a future version. Use one of the above "
1458                 "to silence this warning.",
1459                 FutureWarning,
1460             )
1461 
1462             if orient.startswith("d"):
1463                 orient = "dict"
1464             elif orient.startswith("l"):
1465                 orient = "list"
1466             elif orient.startswith("sp"):
1467                 orient = "split"
1468             elif orient.startswith("s"):
1469                 orient = "series"
1470             elif orient.startswith("r"):
1471                 orient = "records"
1472             elif orient.startswith("i"):
1473                 orient = "index"
1474 
1475         if orient == "dict":
1476             return into_c((k, v.to_dict(into)) for k, v in self.items())
1477 
1478         elif orient == "list":
1479             return into_c((k, v.tolist()) for k, v in self.items())
1480 
1481         elif orient == "split":
1482             return into_c(
1483                 (
1484                     ("index", self.index.tolist()),
1485                     ("columns", self.columns.tolist()),
1486                     (
1487                         "data",
1488                         [
1489                             list(map(com.maybe_box_datetimelike, t))
1490                             for t in self.itertuples(index=False, name=None)
1491                         ],
1492                     ),
1493                 )
1494             )
1495 
1496         elif orient == "series":
1497             return into_c((k, com.maybe_box_datetimelike(v)) for k, v in self.items())
1498 
1499         elif orient == "records":
1500             columns = self.columns.tolist()
1501             rows = (
1502                 dict(zip(columns, row))
1503                 for row in self.itertuples(index=False, name=None)
1504             )
1505             return [
1506                 into_c((k, com.maybe_box_datetimelike(v)) for k, v in row.items())
1507                 for row in rows
1508             ]
1509 
1510         elif orient == "index":
1511             if not self.index.is_unique:
1512                 raise ValueError("DataFrame index must be unique for orient='index'.")
1513             return into_c(
1514                 (t[0], dict(zip(self.columns, t[1:])))
1515                 for t in self.itertuples(name=None)
1516             )
1517 
1518         else:
1519             raise ValueError(f"orient '{orient}' not understood")
1520 
1521     def to_gbq(
1522         self,
1523         destination_table,
1524         project_id=None,
1525         chunksize=None,
1526         reauth=False,
1527         if_exists="fail",
1528         auth_local_webserver=False,
1529         table_schema=None,
1530         location=None,
1531         progress_bar=True,
1532         credentials=None,
1533     ) -> None:
1534         """
1535         Write a DataFrame to a Google BigQuery table.
1536 
1537         This function requires the `pandas-gbq package
1538         <https://pandas-gbq.readthedocs.io>`__.
1539 
1540         See the `How to authenticate with Google BigQuery
1541         <https://pandas-gbq.readthedocs.io/en/latest/howto/authentication.html>`__
1542         guide for authentication instructions.
1543 
1544         Parameters
1545         ----------
1546         destination_table : str
1547             Name of table to be written, in the form ``dataset.tablename``.
1548         project_id : str, optional
1549             Google BigQuery Account project ID. Optional when available from
1550             the environment.
1551         chunksize : int, optional
1552             Number of rows to be inserted in each chunk from the dataframe.
1553             Set to ``None`` to load the whole dataframe at once.
1554         reauth : bool, default False
1555             Force Google BigQuery to re-authenticate the user. This is useful
1556             if multiple accounts are used.
1557         if_exists : str, default 'fail'
1558             Behavior when the destination table exists. Value can be one of:
1559 
1560             ``'fail'``
1561                 If table exists raise pandas_gbq.gbq.TableCreationError.
1562             ``'replace'``
1563                 If table exists, drop it, recreate it, and insert data.
1564             ``'append'``
1565                 If table exists, insert data. Create if does not exist.
1566         auth_local_webserver : bool, default False
1567             Use the `local webserver flow`_ instead of the `console flow`_
1568             when getting user credentials.
1569 
1570             .. _local webserver flow:
1571                 https://google-auth-oauthlib.readthedocs.io/en/latest/reference/google_auth_oauthlib.flow.html#google_auth_oauthlib.flow.InstalledAppFlow.run_local_server
1572             .. _console flow:
1573                 https://google-auth-oauthlib.readthedocs.io/en/latest/reference/google_auth_oauthlib.flow.html#google_auth_oauthlib.flow.InstalledAppFlow.run_console
1574 
1575             *New in version 0.2.0 of pandas-gbq*.
1576         table_schema : list of dicts, optional
1577             List of BigQuery table fields to which according DataFrame
1578             columns conform to, e.g. ``[{'name': 'col1', 'type':
1579             'STRING'},...]``. If schema is not provided, it will be
1580             generated according to dtypes of DataFrame columns. See
1581             BigQuery API documentation on available names of a field.
1582 
1583             *New in version 0.3.1 of pandas-gbq*.
1584         location : str, optional
1585             Location where the load job should run. See the `BigQuery locations
1586             documentation
1587             <https://cloud.google.com/bigquery/docs/dataset-locations>`__ for a
1588             list of available locations. The location must match that of the
1589             target dataset.
1590 
1591             *New in version 0.5.0 of pandas-gbq*.
1592         progress_bar : bool, default True
1593             Use the library `tqdm` to show the progress bar for the upload,
1594             chunk by chunk.
1595 
1596             *New in version 0.5.0 of pandas-gbq*.
1597         credentials : google.auth.credentials.Credentials, optional
1598             Credentials for accessing Google APIs. Use this parameter to
1599             override default credentials, such as to use Compute Engine
1600             :class:`google.auth.compute_engine.Credentials` or Service
1601             Account :class:`google.oauth2.service_account.Credentials`
1602             directly.
1603 
1604             *New in version 0.8.0 of pandas-gbq*.
1605 
1606             .. versionadded:: 0.24.0
1607 
1608         See Also
1609         --------
1610         pandas_gbq.to_gbq : This function in the pandas-gbq library.
1611         read_gbq : Read a DataFrame from Google BigQuery.
1612         """
1613         from pandas.io import gbq
1614 
1615         gbq.to_gbq(
1616             self,
1617             destination_table,
1618             project_id=project_id,
1619             chunksize=chunksize,
1620             reauth=reauth,
1621             if_exists=if_exists,
1622             auth_local_webserver=auth_local_webserver,
1623             table_schema=table_schema,
1624             location=location,
1625             progress_bar=progress_bar,
1626             credentials=credentials,
1627         )
1628 
1629     @classmethod
1630     def from_records(
1631         cls,
1632         data,
1633         index=None,
1634         exclude=None,
1635         columns=None,
1636         coerce_float=False,
1637         nrows=None,
1638     ) -> "DataFrame":
1639         """
1640         Convert structured or record ndarray to DataFrame.
1641 
1642         Creates a DataFrame object from a structured ndarray, sequence of
1643         tuples or dicts, or DataFrame.
1644 
1645         Parameters
1646         ----------
1647         data : structured ndarray, sequence of tuples or dicts, or DataFrame
1648             Structured input data.
1649         index : str, list of fields, array-like
1650             Field of array to use as the index, alternately a specific set of
1651             input labels to use.
1652         exclude : sequence, default None
1653             Columns or fields to exclude.
1654         columns : sequence, default None
1655             Column names to use. If the passed data do not have names
1656             associated with them, this argument provides names for the
1657             columns. Otherwise this argument indicates the order of the columns
1658             in the result (any names not found in the data will become all-NA
1659             columns).
1660         coerce_float : bool, default False
1661             Attempt to convert values of non-string, non-numeric objects (like
1662             decimal.Decimal) to floating point, useful for SQL result sets.
1663         nrows : int, default None
1664             Number of rows to read if data is an iterator.
1665 
1666         Returns
1667         -------
1668         DataFrame
1669 
1670         See Also
1671         --------
1672         DataFrame.from_dict : DataFrame from dict of array-like or dicts.
1673         DataFrame : DataFrame object creation using constructor.
1674 
1675         Examples
1676         --------
1677         Data can be provided as a structured ndarray:
1678 
1679         >>> data = np.array([(3, 'a'), (2, 'b'), (1, 'c'), (0, 'd')],
1680         ...                 dtype=[('col_1', 'i4'), ('col_2', 'U1')])
1681         >>> pd.DataFrame.from_records(data)
1682            col_1 col_2
1683         0      3     a
1684         1      2     b
1685         2      1     c
1686         3      0     d
1687 
1688         Data can be provided as a list of dicts:
1689 
1690         >>> data = [{'col_1': 3, 'col_2': 'a'},
1691         ...         {'col_1': 2, 'col_2': 'b'},
1692         ...         {'col_1': 1, 'col_2': 'c'},
1693         ...         {'col_1': 0, 'col_2': 'd'}]
1694         >>> pd.DataFrame.from_records(data)
1695            col_1 col_2
1696         0      3     a
1697         1      2     b
1698         2      1     c
1699         3      0     d
1700 
1701         Data can be provided as a list of tuples with corresponding columns:
1702 
1703         >>> data = [(3, 'a'), (2, 'b'), (1, 'c'), (0, 'd')]
1704         >>> pd.DataFrame.from_records(data, columns=['col_1', 'col_2'])
1705            col_1 col_2
1706         0      3     a
1707         1      2     b
1708         2      1     c
1709         3      0     d
1710         """
1711         # Make a copy of the input columns so we can modify it
1712         if columns is not None:
1713             columns = ensure_index(columns)
1714 
1715         if is_iterator(data):
1716             if nrows == 0:
1717                 return cls()
1718 
1719             try:
1720                 first_row = next(data)
1721             except StopIteration:
1722                 return cls(index=index, columns=columns)
1723 
1724             dtype = None
1725             if hasattr(first_row, "dtype") and first_row.dtype.names:
1726                 dtype = first_row.dtype
1727 
1728             values = [first_row]
1729 
1730             if nrows is None:
1731                 values += data
1732             else:
1733                 values.extend(itertools.islice(data, nrows - 1))
1734 
1735             if dtype is not None:
1736                 data = np.array(values, dtype=dtype)
1737             else:
1738                 data = values
1739 
1740         if isinstance(data, dict):
1741             if columns is None:
1742                 columns = arr_columns = ensure_index(sorted(data))
1743                 arrays = [data[k] for k in columns]
1744             else:
1745                 arrays = []
1746                 arr_columns = []
1747                 for k, v in data.items():
1748                     if k in columns:
1749                         arr_columns.append(k)
1750                         arrays.append(v)
1751 
1752                 arrays, arr_columns = reorder_arrays(arrays, arr_columns, columns)
1753 
1754         elif isinstance(data, (np.ndarray, DataFrame)):
1755             arrays, columns = to_arrays(data, columns)
1756             if columns is not None:
1757                 columns = ensure_index(columns)
1758             arr_columns = columns
1759         else:
1760             arrays, arr_columns = to_arrays(data, columns, coerce_float=coerce_float)
1761 
1762             arr_columns = ensure_index(arr_columns)
1763             if columns is not None:
1764                 columns = ensure_index(columns)
1765             else:
1766                 columns = arr_columns
1767 
1768         if exclude is None:
1769             exclude = set()
1770         else:
1771             exclude = set(exclude)
1772 
1773         result_index = None
1774         if index is not None:
1775             if isinstance(index, str) or not hasattr(index, "__iter__"):
1776                 i = columns.get_loc(index)
1777                 exclude.add(index)
1778                 if len(arrays) > 0:
1779                     result_index = Index(arrays[i], name=index)
1780                 else:
1781                     result_index = Index([], name=index)
1782             else:
1783                 try:
1784                     index_data = [arrays[arr_columns.get_loc(field)] for field in index]
1785                 except (KeyError, TypeError):
1786                     # raised by get_loc, see GH#29258
1787                     result_index = index
1788                 else:
1789                     result_index = ensure_index_from_sequences(index_data, names=index)
1790                     exclude.update(index)
1791 
1792         if any(exclude):
1793             arr_exclude = [x for x in exclude if x in arr_columns]
1794             to_remove = [arr_columns.get_loc(col) for col in arr_exclude]
1795             arrays = [v for i, v in enumerate(arrays) if i not in to_remove]
1796 
1797             arr_columns = arr_columns.drop(arr_exclude)
1798             columns = columns.drop(exclude)
1799 
1800         mgr = arrays_to_mgr(arrays, arr_columns, result_index, columns)
1801 
1802         return cls(mgr)
1803 
1804     def to_records(
1805         self, index=True, column_dtypes=None, index_dtypes=None
1806     ) -> np.recarray:
1807         """
1808         Convert DataFrame to a NumPy record array.
1809 
1810         Index will be included as the first field of the record array if
1811         requested.
1812 
1813         Parameters
1814         ----------
1815         index : bool, default True
1816             Include index in resulting record array, stored in 'index'
1817             field or using the index label, if set.
1818         column_dtypes : str, type, dict, default None
1819             .. versionadded:: 0.24.0
1820 
1821             If a string or type, the data type to store all columns. If
1822             a dictionary, a mapping of column names and indices (zero-indexed)
1823             to specific data types.
1824         index_dtypes : str, type, dict, default None
1825             .. versionadded:: 0.24.0
1826 
1827             If a string or type, the data type to store all index levels. If
1828             a dictionary, a mapping of index level names and indices
1829             (zero-indexed) to specific data types.
1830 
1831             This mapping is applied only if `index=True`.
1832 
1833         Returns
1834         -------
1835         numpy.recarray
1836             NumPy ndarray with the DataFrame labels as fields and each row
1837             of the DataFrame as entries.
1838 
1839         See Also
1840         --------
1841         DataFrame.from_records: Convert structured or record ndarray
1842             to DataFrame.
1843         numpy.recarray: An ndarray that allows field access using
1844             attributes, analogous to typed columns in a
1845             spreadsheet.
1846 
1847         Examples
1848         --------
1849         >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'A': [1, 2], 'B': [0.5, 0.75]},
1850         ...                   index=['a', 'b'])
1851         >>> df
1852            A     B
1853         a  1  0.50
1854         b  2  0.75
1855         >>> df.to_records()
1856         rec.array([('a', 1, 0.5 ), ('b', 2, 0.75)],
1857                   dtype=[('index', 'O'), ('A', '<i8'), ('B', '<f8')])
1858 
1859         If the DataFrame index has no label then the recarray field name
1860         is set to 'index'. If the index has a label then this is used as the
1861         field name:
1862 
1863         >>> df.index = df.index.rename("I")
1864         >>> df.to_records()
1865         rec.array([('a', 1, 0.5 ), ('b', 2, 0.75)],
1866                   dtype=[('I', 'O'), ('A', '<i8'), ('B', '<f8')])
1867 
1868         The index can be excluded from the record array:
1869 
1870         >>> df.to_records(index=False)
1871         rec.array([(1, 0.5 ), (2, 0.75)],
1872                   dtype=[('A', '<i8'), ('B', '<f8')])
1873 
1874         Data types can be specified for the columns:
1875 
1876         >>> df.to_records(column_dtypes={"A": "int32"})
1877         rec.array([('a', 1, 0.5 ), ('b', 2, 0.75)],
1878                   dtype=[('I', 'O'), ('A', '<i4'), ('B', '<f8')])
1879 
1880         As well as for the index:
1881 
1882         >>> df.to_records(index_dtypes="<S2")
1883         rec.array([(b'a', 1, 0.5 ), (b'b', 2, 0.75)],
1884                   dtype=[('I', 'S2'), ('A', '<i8'), ('B', '<f8')])
1885 
1886         >>> index_dtypes = f"<S{df.index.str.len().max()}"
1887         >>> df.to_records(index_dtypes=index_dtypes)
1888         rec.array([(b'a', 1, 0.5 ), (b'b', 2, 0.75)],
1889                   dtype=[('I', 'S1'), ('A', '<i8'), ('B', '<f8')])
1890         """
1891         if index:
1892             if isinstance(self.index, MultiIndex):
1893                 # array of tuples to numpy cols. copy copy copy
1894                 ix_vals = list(map(np.array, zip(*self.index._values)))
1895             else:
1896                 ix_vals = [self.index.values]
1897 
1898             arrays = ix_vals + [
1899                 np.asarray(self.iloc[:, i]) for i in range(len(self.columns))
1900             ]
1901 
1902             count = 0
1903             index_names = list(self.index.names)
1904 
1905             if isinstance(self.index, MultiIndex):
1906                 for i, n in enumerate(index_names):
1907                     if n is None:
1908                         index_names[i] = f"level_{count}"
1909                         count += 1
1910             elif index_names[0] is None:
1911                 index_names = ["index"]
1912 
1913             names = [str(name) for name in itertools.chain(index_names, self.columns)]
1914         else:
1915             arrays = [np.asarray(self.iloc[:, i]) for i in range(len(self.columns))]
1916             names = [str(c) for c in self.columns]
1917             index_names = []
1918 
1919         index_len = len(index_names)
1920         formats = []
1921 
1922         for i, v in enumerate(arrays):
1923             index = i
1924 
1925             # When the names and arrays are collected, we
1926             # first collect those in the DataFrame's index,
1927             # followed by those in its columns.
1928             #
1929             # Thus, the total length of the array is:
1930             # len(index_names) + len(DataFrame.columns).
1931             #
1932             # This check allows us to see whether we are
1933             # handling a name / array in the index or column.
1934             if index < index_len:
1935                 dtype_mapping = index_dtypes
1936                 name = index_names[index]
1937             else:
1938                 index -= index_len
1939                 dtype_mapping = column_dtypes
1940                 name = self.columns[index]
1941 
1942             # We have a dictionary, so we get the data type
1943             # associated with the index or column (which can
1944             # be denoted by its name in the DataFrame or its
1945             # position in DataFrame's array of indices or
1946             # columns, whichever is applicable.
1947             if is_dict_like(dtype_mapping):
1948                 if name in dtype_mapping:
1949                     dtype_mapping = dtype_mapping[name]
1950                 elif index in dtype_mapping:
1951                     dtype_mapping = dtype_mapping[index]
1952                 else:
1953                     dtype_mapping = None
1954 
1955             # If no mapping can be found, use the array's
1956             # dtype attribute for formatting.
1957             #
1958             # A valid dtype must either be a type or
1959             # string naming a type.
1960             if dtype_mapping is None:
1961                 formats.append(v.dtype)
1962             elif isinstance(dtype_mapping, (type, np.dtype, str)):
1963                 formats.append(dtype_mapping)
1964             else:
1965                 element = "row" if i < index_len else "column"
1966                 msg = f"Invalid dtype {dtype_mapping} specified for {element} {name}"
1967                 raise ValueError(msg)
1968 
1969         return np.rec.fromarrays(arrays, dtype={"names": names, "formats": formats})
1970 
1971     @classmethod
1972     def _from_arrays(
1973         cls,
1974         arrays,
1975         columns,
1976         index,
1977         dtype: Optional[Dtype] = None,
1978         verify_integrity: bool = True,
1979     ) -> "DataFrame":
1980         """
1981         Create DataFrame from a list of arrays corresponding to the columns.
1982 
1983         Parameters
1984         ----------
1985         arrays : list-like of arrays
1986             Each array in the list corresponds to one column, in order.
1987         columns : list-like, Index
1988             The column names for the resulting DataFrame.
1989         index : list-like, Index
1990             The rows labels for the resulting DataFrame.
1991         dtype : dtype, optional
1992             Optional dtype to enforce for all arrays.
1993         verify_integrity : bool, default True
1994             Validate and homogenize all input. If set to False, it is assumed
1995             that all elements of `arrays` are actual arrays how they will be
1996             stored in a block (numpy ndarray or ExtensionArray), have the same
1997             length as and are aligned with the index, and that `columns` and
1998             `index` are ensured to be an Index object.
1999 
2000         Returns
2001         -------
2002         DataFrame
2003         """
2004         if dtype is not None:
2005             dtype = pandas_dtype(dtype)
2006 
2007         mgr = arrays_to_mgr(
2008             arrays,
2009             columns,
2010             index,
2011             columns,
2012             dtype=dtype,
2013             verify_integrity=verify_integrity,
2014         )
2015         return cls(mgr)
2016 
2017     @deprecate_kwarg(old_arg_name="fname", new_arg_name="path")
2018     def to_stata(
2019         self,
2020         path: FilePathOrBuffer,
2021         convert_dates: Optional[Dict[Label, str]] = None,
2022         write_index: bool = True,
2023         byteorder: Optional[str] = None,
2024         time_stamp: Optional[datetime.datetime] = None,
2025         data_label: Optional[str] = None,
2026         variable_labels: Optional[Dict[Label, str]] = None,
2027         version: Optional[int] = 114,
2028         convert_strl: Optional[Sequence[Label]] = None,
2029         compression: Union[str, Mapping[str, str], None] = "infer",
2030     ) -> None:
2031         """
2032         Export DataFrame object to Stata dta format.
2033 
2034         Writes the DataFrame to a Stata dataset file.
2035         "dta" files contain a Stata dataset.
2036 
2037         Parameters
2038         ----------
2039         path : str, buffer or path object
2040             String, path object (pathlib.Path or py._path.local.LocalPath) or
2041             object implementing a binary write() function. If using a buffer
2042             then the buffer will not be automatically closed after the file
2043             data has been written.
2044 
2045             .. versionchanged:: 1.0.0
2046 
2047             Previously this was "fname"
2048 
2049         convert_dates : dict
2050             Dictionary mapping columns containing datetime types to stata
2051             internal format to use when writing the dates. Options are 'tc',
2052             'td', 'tm', 'tw', 'th', 'tq', 'ty'. Column can be either an integer
2053             or a name. Datetime columns that do not have a conversion type
2054             specified will be converted to 'tc'. Raises NotImplementedError if
2055             a datetime column has timezone information.
2056         write_index : bool
2057             Write the index to Stata dataset.
2058         byteorder : str
2059             Can be ">", "<", "little", or "big". default is `sys.byteorder`.
2060         time_stamp : datetime
2061             A datetime to use as file creation date.  Default is the current
2062             time.
2063         data_label : str, optional
2064             A label for the data set.  Must be 80 characters or smaller.
2065         variable_labels : dict
2066             Dictionary containing columns as keys and variable labels as
2067             values. Each label must be 80 characters or smaller.
2068         version : {114, 117, 118, 119, None}, default 114
2069             Version to use in the output dta file. Set to None to let pandas
2070             decide between 118 or 119 formats depending on the number of
2071             columns in the frame. Version 114 can be read by Stata 10 and
2072             later. Version 117 can be read by Stata 13 or later. Version 118
2073             is supported in Stata 14 and later. Version 119 is supported in
2074             Stata 15 and later. Version 114 limits string variables to 244
2075             characters or fewer while versions 117 and later allow strings
2076             with lengths up to 2,000,000 characters. Versions 118 and 119
2077             support Unicode characters, and version 119 supports more than
2078             32,767 variables.
2079 
2080             .. versionadded:: 0.23.0
2081             .. versionchanged:: 1.0.0
2082 
2083                 Added support for formats 118 and 119.
2084 
2085         convert_strl : list, optional
2086             List of column names to convert to string columns to Stata StrL
2087             format. Only available if version is 117.  Storing strings in the
2088             StrL format can produce smaller dta files if strings have more than
2089             8 characters and values are repeated.
2090 
2091             .. versionadded:: 0.23.0
2092 
2093         compression : str or dict, default 'infer'
2094             For on-the-fly compression of the output dta. If string, specifies
2095             compression mode. If dict, value at key 'method' specifies
2096             compression mode. Compression mode must be one of {'infer', 'gzip',
2097             'bz2', 'zip', 'xz', None}. If compression mode is 'infer' and
2098             `fname` is path-like, then detect compression from the following
2099             extensions: '.gz', '.bz2', '.zip', or '.xz' (otherwise no
2100             compression). If dict and compression mode is one of {'zip',
2101             'gzip', 'bz2'}, or inferred as one of the above, other entries
2102             passed as additional compression options.
2103 
2104             .. versionadded:: 1.1.0
2105 
2106         Raises
2107         ------
2108         NotImplementedError
2109             * If datetimes contain timezone information
2110             * Column dtype is not representable in Stata
2111         ValueError
2112             * Columns listed in convert_dates are neither datetime64[ns]
2113               or datetime.datetime
2114             * Column listed in convert_dates is not in DataFrame
2115             * Categorical label contains more than 32,000 characters
2116 
2117         See Also
2118         --------
2119         read_stata : Import Stata data files.
2120         io.stata.StataWriter : Low-level writer for Stata data files.
2121         io.stata.StataWriter117 : Low-level writer for version 117 files.
2122 
2123         Examples
2124         --------
2125         >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'animal': ['falcon', 'parrot', 'falcon',
2126         ...                               'parrot'],
2127         ...                    'speed': [350, 18, 361, 15]})
2128         >>> df.to_stata('animals.dta')  # doctest: +SKIP
2129         """
2130         if version not in (114, 117, 118, 119, None):
2131             raise ValueError("Only formats 114, 117, 118 and 119 are supported.")
2132         if version == 114:
2133             if convert_strl is not None:
2134                 raise ValueError("strl is not supported in format 114")
2135             from pandas.io.stata import StataWriter as statawriter
2136         elif version == 117:
2137             # mypy: Name 'statawriter' already defined (possibly by an import)
2138             from pandas.io.stata import StataWriter117 as statawriter  # type: ignore
2139         else:  # versions 118 and 119
2140             # mypy: Name 'statawriter' already defined (possibly by an import)
2141             from pandas.io.stata import StataWriterUTF8 as statawriter  # type:ignore
2142 
2143         kwargs: Dict[str, Any] = {}
2144         if version is None or version >= 117:
2145             # strl conversion is only supported >= 117
2146             kwargs["convert_strl"] = convert_strl
2147         if version is None or version >= 118:
2148             # Specifying the version is only supported for UTF8 (118 or 119)
2149             kwargs["version"] = version
2150 
2151         # mypy: Too many arguments for "StataWriter"
2152         writer = statawriter(  # type: ignore
2153             path,
2154             self,
2155             convert_dates=convert_dates,
2156             byteorder=byteorder,
2157             time_stamp=time_stamp,
2158             data_label=data_label,
2159             write_index=write_index,
2160             variable_labels=variable_labels,
2161             compression=compression,
2162             **kwargs,
2163         )
2164         writer.write_file()
2165

2178             `compression_level`, `chunksize` and `version` keywords.
2179 
2180             .. versionadded:: 1.1.0

2182         from pandas.io.feather_format import to_feather

2186     @Appender(
2187         """
2188         Examples
2189         --------
2190         >>> df = pd.DataFrame(
2191         ...     data={"animal_1": ["elk", "pig"], "animal_2": ["dog", "quetzal"]}
2192         ... )
2193         >>> print(df.to_markdown())
2194         |    | animal_1   | animal_2   |
2195         |---:|:-----------|:-----------|
2196         |  0 | elk        | dog        |
2197         |  1 | pig        | quetzal    |
2198 
2199         Output markdown with a tabulate option.
2200 
2201         >>> print(df.to_markdown(tablefmt="grid"))
2202         +----+------------+------------+
2203         |    | animal_1   | animal_2   |
2204         +====+============+============+
2205         |  0 | elk        | dog        |
2206         +----+------------+------------+
2207         |  1 | pig        | quetzal    |
2208         +----+------------+------------+
2209         """
2210     )
2211     @Substitution(klass="DataFrame")
2212     @Appender(_shared_docs["to_markdown"])
2213     def to_markdown(
2214         self, buf: Optional[IO[str]] = None, mode: Optional[str] = None, **kwargs
2215     ) -> Optional[str]:
2216         kwargs.setdefault("headers", "keys")
2217         kwargs.setdefault("tablefmt", "pipe")
2218         tabulate = import_optional_dependency("tabulate")
2219         result = tabulate.tabulate(self, **kwargs)
2220         if buf is None:
2221             return result
2222         buf, _, _, _ = get_filepath_or_buffer(buf, mode=mode)
2223         assert buf is not None  # Help mypy.
2224         buf.writelines(result)
2225         return None

2227     @deprecate_kwarg(old_arg_name="fname", new_arg_name="path")
2228     def to_parquet(
2229         self,
2230         path,
2231         engine="auto",
2232         compression="snappy",
2233         index=None,
2234         partition_cols=None,
2235         **kwargs,
2236     ) -> None:
2237         """
2238         Write a DataFrame to the binary parquet format.
2239 
2240         This function writes the dataframe as a `parquet file
2241         <https://parquet.apache.org/>`_. You can choose different parquet
2242         backends, and have the option of compression. See
2243         :ref:`the user guide <io.parquet>` for more details.
2244 
2245         Parameters
2246         ----------
2247         path : str
2248             File path or Root Directory path. Will be used as Root Directory
2249             path while writing a partitioned dataset.
2250 
2251             .. versionchanged:: 1.0.0
2252 
2253             Previously this was "fname"
2254 
2255         engine : {'auto', 'pyarrow', 'fastparquet'}, default 'auto'
2256             Parquet library to use. If 'auto', then the option
2257             ``io.parquet.engine`` is used. The default ``io.parquet.engine``
2258             behavior is to try 'pyarrow', falling back to 'fastparquet' if
2259             'pyarrow' is unavailable.
2260         compression : {'snappy', 'gzip', 'brotli', None}, default 'snappy'
2261             Name of the compression to use. Use ``None`` for no compression.
2262         index : bool, default None
2263             If ``True``, include the dataframe's index(es) in the file output.
2264             If ``False``, they will not be written to the file.
2265             If ``None``, similar to ``True`` the dataframe's index(es)
2266             will be saved. However, instead of being saved as values,
2267             the RangeIndex will be stored as a range in the metadata so it
2268             doesn't require much space and is faster. Other indexes will
2269             be included as columns in the file output.
2270 
2271             .. versionadded:: 0.24.0
2272 
2273         partition_cols : list, optional, default None
2274             Column names by which to partition the dataset.
2275             Columns are partitioned in the order they are given.
2276 
2277             .. versionadded:: 0.24.0
2278 
2279         **kwargs
2280             Additional arguments passed to the parquet library. See
2281             :ref:`pandas io <io.parquet>` for more details.
2282 
2283         See Also
2284         --------
2285         read_parquet : Read a parquet file.
2286         DataFrame.to_csv : Write a csv file.
2287         DataFrame.to_sql : Write to a sql table.
2288         DataFrame.to_hdf : Write to hdf.
2289 
2290         Notes
2291         -----
2292         This function requires either the `fastparquet
2293         <https://pypi.org/project/fastparquet>`_ or `pyarrow
2294         <https://arrow.apache.org/docs/python/>`_ library.
2295 
2296         Examples
2297         --------
2298         >>> df = pd.DataFrame(data={'col1': [1, 2], 'col2': [3, 4]})
2299         >>> df.to_parquet('df.parquet.gzip',
2300         ...               compression='gzip')  # doctest: +SKIP
2301         >>> pd.read_parquet('df.parquet.gzip')  # doctest: +SKIP
2302            col1  col2
2303         0     1     3
2304         1     2     4
2305 
2306         If you want to get a buffer to the parquet content you can use a io.BytesIO
2307         object, as long as you don't use partition_cols, which creates multiple files.
2308 
2309         >>> import io
2310         >>> f = io.BytesIO()
2311         >>> df.to_parquet(f)
2312         >>> f.seek(0)
2313         0
2314         >>> content = f.read()
2315         """
2316         from pandas.io.parquet import to_parquet
2317 
2318         to_parquet(
2319             self,
2320             path,
2321             engine,
2322             compression=compression,
2323             index=index,
2324             partition_cols=partition_cols,
2325             **kwargs,
2326         )

2328     @Substitution(
2329         header_type="bool",
2330         header="Whether to print column labels, default True",
2331         col_space_type="str or int",
2332         col_space="The minimum width of each column in CSS length "

2337     @Substitution(shared_params=fmt.common_docstring, returns=fmt.return_docstring)
2338     def to_html(
2339         self,
2340         buf=None,
2341         columns=None,
2342         col_space=None,
2343         header=True,
2344         index=True,
2345         na_rep="NaN",
2346         formatters=None,
2347         float_format=None,
2348         sparsify=None,
2349         index_names=True,
2350         justify=None,
2351         max_rows=None,
2352         max_cols=None,
2353         show_dimensions=False,
2354         decimal=".",
2355         bold_rows=True,
2356         classes=None,
2357         escape=True,
2358         notebook=False,
2359         border=None,
2360         table_id=None,
2361         render_links=False,
2362         encoding=None,
2363     ):
2364         """
2365         Render a DataFrame as an HTML table.
2366         %(shared_params)s
2367         bold_rows : bool, default True
2368             Make the row labels bold in the output.
2369         classes : str or list or tuple, default None
2370             CSS class(es) to apply to the resulting html table.
2371         escape : bool, default True
2372             Convert the characters <, >, and & to HTML-safe sequences.
2373         notebook : {True, False}, default False
2374             Whether the generated HTML is for IPython Notebook.
2375         border : int
2376             A ``border=border`` attribute is included in the opening
2377             `<table>` tag. Default ``pd.options.display.html.border``.
2378         encoding : str, default "utf-8"
2379             Set character encoding.
2380 
2381             .. versionadded:: 1.0
2382 
2383         table_id : str, optional
2384             A css id is included in the opening `<table>` tag if specified.
2385 
2386             .. versionadded:: 0.23.0
2387 
2388         render_links : bool, default False
2389             Convert URLs to HTML links.
2390 
2391             .. versionadded:: 0.24.0
2392         %(returns)s
2393         See Also
2394         --------
2395         to_string : Convert DataFrame to a string.
2396         """
2397         if justify is not None and justify not in fmt._VALID_JUSTIFY_PARAMETERS:
2398             raise ValueError("Invalid value for justify parameter")
2399 
2400         formatter = fmt.DataFrameFormatter(
2401             self,
2402             columns=columns,
2403             col_space=col_space,
2404             na_rep=na_rep,
2405             formatters=formatters,
2406             float_format=float_format,
2407             sparsify=sparsify,
2408             justify=justify,
2409             index_names=index_names,
2410             header=header,
2411             index=index,
2412             bold_rows=bold_rows,
2413             escape=escape,
2414             max_rows=max_rows,
2415             max_cols=max_cols,
2416             show_dimensions=show_dimensions,
2417             decimal=decimal,
2418             table_id=table_id,
2419             render_links=render_links,
2420         )
2421         # TODO: a generic formatter wld b in DataFrameFormatter
2422         return formatter.to_html(
2423             buf=buf,
2424             classes=classes,
2425             notebook=notebook,
2426             border=border,
2427             encoding=encoding,
2428         )

2431     @Substitution(
2432         klass="DataFrame",
2433         type_sub=" and columns",
2434         max_cols_sub=(
2435             """max_cols : int, optional
