2543 
2544     def memory_usage(self, index=True, deep=False) -> Series:
2545         """
2546         Return the memory usage of each column in bytes.
2547 
2548         The memory usage can optionally include the contribution of
2549         the index and elements of `object` dtype.
2550 
2551         This value is displayed in `DataFrame.info` by default. This can be
2552         suppressed by setting ``pandas.options.display.memory_usage`` to False.
2553 
2554         Parameters
2555         ----------
2556         index : bool, default True
2557             Specifies whether to include the memory usage of the DataFrame's
2558             index in returned Series. If ``index=True``, the memory usage of
2559             the index is the first item in the output.
2560         deep : bool, default False
2561             If True, introspect the data deeply by interrogating
2562             `object` dtypes for system-level memory consumption, and include
2563             it in the returned values.
2564 
2565         Returns
2566         -------
2567         Series
2568             A Series whose index is the original column names and whose values
2569             is the memory usage of each column in bytes.
2570 
2571         See Also
2572         --------
2573         numpy.ndarray.nbytes : Total bytes consumed by the elements of an
2574             ndarray.
2575         Series.memory_usage : Bytes consumed by a Series.
2576         Categorical : Memory-efficient array for string values with
2577             many repeated values.
2578         DataFrame.info : Concise summary of a DataFrame.
2579 
2580         Examples
2581         --------
2582         >>> dtypes = ['int64', 'float64', 'complex128', 'object', 'bool']
2583         >>> data = dict([(t, np.ones(shape=5000).astype(t))
2584         ...              for t in dtypes])
2585         >>> df = pd.DataFrame(data)
2586         >>> df.head()
2587            int64  float64            complex128  object  bool
2588         0      1      1.0    1.000000+0.000000j       1  True
2589         1      1      1.0    1.000000+0.000000j       1  True
2590         2      1      1.0    1.000000+0.000000j       1  True
2591         3      1      1.0    1.000000+0.000000j       1  True
2592         4      1      1.0    1.000000+0.000000j       1  True
2593 
2594         >>> df.memory_usage()
2595         Index           128
2596         int64         40000
2597         float64       40000
2598         complex128    80000
2599         object        40000
2600         bool           5000
2601         dtype: int64
2602 
2603         >>> df.memory_usage(index=False)
2604         int64         40000
2605         float64       40000
2606         complex128    80000
2607         object        40000
2608         bool           5000
2609         dtype: int64
2610 
2611         The memory footprint of `object` dtype columns is ignored by default:
2612 
2613         >>> df.memory_usage(deep=True)
2614         Index            128
2615         int64          40000
2616         float64        40000
2617         complex128     80000
2618         object        160000
2619         bool            5000
2620         dtype: int64
2621 
2622         Use a Categorical for efficient storage of an object-dtype column with
2623         many repeated values.
2624 
2625         >>> df['object'].astype('category').memory_usage(deep=True)
2626         5216
2627         """
2628         result = self._constructor_sliced(
2629             [c.memory_usage(index=False, deep=deep) for col, c in self.items()],
2630             index=self.columns,
2631         )
2632         if index:
2633             result = self._constructor_sliced(
2634                 self.index.memory_usage(deep=deep), index=["Index"]
2635             ).append(result)
2636         return result
2637 
2638     def transpose(self, *args, copy: bool = False) -> "DataFrame":
2639         """
2640         Transpose index and columns.
2641 
2642         Reflect the DataFrame over its main diagonal by writing rows as columns
2643         and vice-versa. The property :attr:`.T` is an accessor to the method
2644         :meth:`transpose`.
2645 
2646         Parameters
2647         ----------
2648         *args : tuple, optional
2649             Accepted for compatibility with NumPy.
2650         copy : bool, default False
2651             Whether to copy the data after transposing, even for DataFrames
2652             with a single dtype.
2653 
2654             Note that a copy is always required for mixed dtype DataFrames,
2655             or for DataFrames with any extension types.
2656 
2657         Returns
2658         -------
2659         DataFrame
2660             The transposed DataFrame.
2661 
2662         See Also
2663         --------
2664         numpy.transpose : Permute the dimensions of a given array.
2665 
2666         Notes
2667         -----
2668         Transposing a DataFrame with mixed dtypes will result in a homogeneous
2669         DataFrame with the `object` dtype. In such a case, a copy of the data
2670         is always made.
2671 
2672         Examples
2673         --------
2674         **Square DataFrame with homogeneous dtype**
2675 
2676         >>> d1 = {'col1': [1, 2], 'col2': [3, 4]}
2677         >>> df1 = pd.DataFrame(data=d1)
2678         >>> df1
2679            col1  col2
2680         0     1     3
2681         1     2     4
2682 
2683         >>> df1_transposed = df1.T # or df1.transpose()
2684         >>> df1_transposed
2685               0  1
2686         col1  1  2
2687         col2  3  4
2688 
2689         When the dtype is homogeneous in the original DataFrame, we get a
2690         transposed DataFrame with the same dtype:
2691 
2692         >>> df1.dtypes
2693         col1    int64
2694         col2    int64
2695         dtype: object
2696         >>> df1_transposed.dtypes
2697         0    int64
2698         1    int64
2699         dtype: object
2700 
2701         **Non-square DataFrame with mixed dtypes**
2702 
2703         >>> d2 = {'name': ['Alice', 'Bob'],
2704         ...       'score': [9.5, 8],
2705         ...       'employed': [False, True],
2706         ...       'kids': [0, 0]}
2707         >>> df2 = pd.DataFrame(data=d2)
2708         >>> df2
2709             name  score  employed  kids
2710         0  Alice    9.5     False     0
2711         1    Bob    8.0      True     0
2712 
2713         >>> df2_transposed = df2.T # or df2.transpose()
2714         >>> df2_transposed
2715                       0     1
2716         name      Alice   Bob
2717         score       9.5     8
2718         employed  False  True
2719         kids          0     0
2720 
2721         When the DataFrame has mixed dtypes, we get a transposed DataFrame with
2722         the `object` dtype:
2723 
2724         >>> df2.dtypes
2725         name         object
2726         score       float64
2727         employed       bool
2728         kids          int64
2729         dtype: object
2730         >>> df2_transposed.dtypes
2731         0    object
2732         1    object
2733         dtype: object
2734         """
2735         nv.validate_transpose(args, dict())
2736         # construct the args
2737 
2738         dtypes = list(self.dtypes)
2739         if self._is_homogeneous_type and dtypes and is_extension_array_dtype(dtypes[0]):
2740             # We have EAs with the same dtype. We can preserve that dtype in transpose.
2741             dtype = dtypes[0]
2742             arr_type = dtype.construct_array_type()
2743             values = self.values
2744 
2745             new_values = [arr_type._from_sequence(row, dtype=dtype) for row in values]
2746             result = self._constructor(
2747                 dict(zip(self.index, new_values)), index=self.columns
2748             )
2749 
2750         else:
2751             new_values = self.values.T
2752             if copy:
2753                 new_values = new_values.copy()
2754             result = self._constructor(
2755                 new_values, index=self.columns, columns=self.index
2756             )
2757 
2758         return result.__finalize__(self, method="transpose")
2759 
2760     @property
2761     def T(self) -> "DataFrame":
2762         return self.transpose()
2763 
2764     # ----------------------------------------------------------------------
2765     # Indexing Methods
2766 
2767     def _ixs(self, i: int, axis: int = 0):
2768         """
2769         Parameters
2770         ----------
2771         i : int
2772         axis : int
2773 
2774         Notes
2775         -----
2776         If slice passed, the resulting data will be a view.
2777         """
2778         # irow
2779         if axis == 0:
2780             new_values = self._mgr.fast_xs(i)
2781 
2782             # if we are a copy, mark as such
2783             copy = isinstance(new_values, np.ndarray) and new_values.base is None
2784             result = self._constructor_sliced(
2785                 new_values,
2786                 index=self.columns,
2787                 name=self.index[i],
2788                 dtype=new_values.dtype,
2789             )
2790             result._set_is_copy(self, copy=copy)
2791             return result
2792 
2793         # icol
2794         else:
2795             label = self.columns[i]
2796 
2797             values = self._mgr.iget(i)
2798             result = self._box_col_values(values, i)
2799 
2800             # this is a cached value, mark it so
2801             result._set_as_cached(label, self)
2802 
2803             return result
2804 
2805     def _get_column_array(self, i: int) -> ArrayLike:
2806         """
2807         Get the values of the i'th column (ndarray or ExtensionArray, as stored
2808         in the Block)
2809         """
2810         return self._data.iget_values(i)
2811 
2812     def _iter_column_arrays(self) -> Iterator[ArrayLike]:
2813         """
2814         Iterate over the arrays of all columns in order.
2815         This returns the values as stored in the Block (ndarray or ExtensionArray).
2816         """
2817         for i in range(len(self.columns)):
2818             yield self._get_column_array(i)
2819 
2820     def __getitem__(self, key):
2821         key = lib.item_from_zerodim(key)
2822         key = com.apply_if_callable(key, self)
2823 
2824         if is_hashable(key):
2825             # shortcut if the key is in columns
2826             if self.columns.is_unique and key in self.columns:
2827                 if self.columns.nlevels > 1:
2828                     return self._getitem_multilevel(key)
2829                 return self._get_item_cache(key)
2830 
2831         # Do we have a slicer (on rows)?
2832         indexer = convert_to_index_sliceable(self, key)
2833         if indexer is not None:
2834             # either we have a slice or we have a string that can be converted
2835             #  to a slice for partial-string date indexing
2836             return self._slice(indexer, axis=0)
2837 
2838         # Do we have a (boolean) DataFrame?
2839         if isinstance(key, DataFrame):
2840             return self.where(key)
2841 
2842         # Do we have a (boolean) 1d indexer?
2843         if com.is_bool_indexer(key):
2844             return self._getitem_bool_array(key)
2845 
2846         # We are left with two options: a single key, and a collection of keys,
2847         # We interpret tuples as collections only for non-MultiIndex
2848         is_single_key = isinstance(key, tuple) or not is_list_like(key)
2849 
2850         if is_single_key:
2851             if self.columns.nlevels > 1:
2852                 return self._getitem_multilevel(key)
2853             indexer = self.columns.get_loc(key)
2854             if is_integer(indexer):
2855                 indexer = [indexer]
2856         else:
2857             if is_iterator(key):
2858                 key = list(key)
2859             indexer = self.loc._get_listlike_indexer(key, axis=1, raise_missing=True)[1]
2860 
2861         # take() does not accept boolean indexers
2862         if getattr(indexer, "dtype", None) == bool:
2863             indexer = np.where(indexer)[0]
2864 
2865         data = self._take_with_is_copy(indexer, axis=1)
2866 
2867         if is_single_key:
2868             # What does looking for a single key in a non-unique index return?
2869             # The behavior is inconsistent. It returns a Series, except when
2870             # - the key itself is repeated (test on data.shape, #9519), or
2871             # - we have a MultiIndex on columns (test on self.columns, #21309)
2872             if data.shape[1] == 1 and not isinstance(self.columns, MultiIndex):
2873                 data = data[key]
2874 
2875         return data
2876 
2877     def _getitem_bool_array(self, key):
2878         # also raises Exception if object array with NA values
2879         # warning here just in case -- previously __setitem__ was
2880         # reindexing but __getitem__ was not; it seems more reasonable to
2881         # go with the __setitem__ behavior since that is more consistent
2882         # with all other indexing behavior
2883         if isinstance(key, Series) and not key.index.equals(self.index):
2884             warnings.warn(
2885                 "Boolean Series key will be reindexed to match DataFrame index.",
2886                 UserWarning,
2887                 stacklevel=3,
2888             )
2889         elif len(key) != len(self.index):
2890             raise ValueError(
2891                 f"Item wrong length {len(key)} instead of {len(self.index)}."
2892             )
2893 
2894         # check_bool_indexer will throw exception if Series key cannot
2895         # be reindexed to match DataFrame rows
2896         key = check_bool_indexer(self.index, key)
2897         indexer = key.nonzero()[0]
2898         return self._take_with_is_copy(indexer, axis=0)
2899 
2900     def _getitem_multilevel(self, key):
2901         # self.columns is a MultiIndex
2902         loc = self.columns.get_loc(key)
2903         if isinstance(loc, (slice, np.ndarray)):
2904             new_columns = self.columns[loc]
2905             result_columns = maybe_droplevels(new_columns, key)
2906             if self._is_mixed_type:
2907                 result = self.reindex(columns=new_columns)
2908                 result.columns = result_columns
2909             else:
2910                 new_values = self.values[:, loc]
2911                 result = self._constructor(
2912                     new_values, index=self.index, columns=result_columns
2913                 )
2914                 result = result.__finalize__(self)
2915 
2916             # If there is only one column being returned, and its name is
2917             # either an empty string, or a tuple with an empty string as its
2918             # first element, then treat the empty string as a placeholder
2919             # and return the column as if the user had provided that empty
2920             # string in the key. If the result is a Series, exclude the
2921             # implied empty string from its name.
2922             if len(result.columns) == 1:
2923                 top = result.columns[0]
2924                 if isinstance(top, tuple):
2925                     top = top[0]
2926                 if top == "":
2927                     result = result[""]
2928                     if isinstance(result, Series):
2929                         result = self._constructor_sliced(
2930                             result, index=self.index, name=key
2931                         )
2932 
2933             result._set_is_copy(self)
2934             return result
2935         else:
2936             # loc is neither a slice nor ndarray, so must be an int
2937             return self._ixs(loc, axis=1)
2938 
2939     def _get_value(self, index, col, takeable: bool = False):
2940         """
2941         Quickly retrieve single value at passed column and index.
2942 
2943         Parameters
2944         ----------
2945         index : row label
2946         col : column label
2947         takeable : interpret the index/col as indexers, default False
2948 
2949         Returns
2950         -------
2951         scalar
2952         """
2953         if takeable:
2954             series = self._ixs(col, axis=1)
2955             return series._values[index]
2956 
2957         series = self._get_item_cache(col)
2958         engine = self.index._engine
2959 
2960         try:
2961             loc = engine.get_loc(index)
2962             return series._values[loc]
2963         except KeyError:
2964             # GH 20629
2965             if self.index.nlevels > 1:
2966                 # partial indexing forbidden
2967                 raise
2968 
2969         # we cannot handle direct indexing
2970         # use positional
2971         col = self.columns.get_loc(col)
2972         index = self.index.get_loc(index)
2973         return self._get_value(index, col, takeable=True)
2974 
2975     def __setitem__(self, key, value):
2976         key = com.apply_if_callable(key, self)
2977 
2978         # see if we can slice the rows
2979         indexer = convert_to_index_sliceable(self, key)
2980         if indexer is not None:
2981             # either we have a slice or we have a string that can be converted
2982             #  to a slice for partial-string date indexing
2983             return self._setitem_slice(indexer, value)
2984 
2985         if isinstance(key, DataFrame) or getattr(key, "ndim", None) == 2:
2986             self._setitem_frame(key, value)
2987         elif isinstance(key, (Series, np.ndarray, list, Index)):
2988             self._setitem_array(key, value)
2989         else:
2990             # set column
2991             self._set_item(key, value)
2992 
2993     def _setitem_slice(self, key: slice, value):
2994         # NB: we can't just use self.loc[key] = value because that
2995         #  operates on labels and we need to operate positional for
2996         #  backwards-compat, xref GH#31469
2997         self._check_setitem_copy()
2998         self.iloc._setitem_with_indexer(key, value)
2999 
3000     def _setitem_array(self, key, value):
3001         # also raises Exception if object array with NA values
3002         if com.is_bool_indexer(key):
3003             if len(key) != len(self.index):
3004                 raise ValueError(
3005                     f"Item wrong length {len(key)} instead of {len(self.index)}!"
3006                 )
3007             key = check_bool_indexer(self.index, key)
3008             indexer = key.nonzero()[0]
3009             self._check_setitem_copy()
3010             self.iloc._setitem_with_indexer(indexer, value)
3011         else:
3012             if isinstance(value, DataFrame):
3013                 if len(value.columns) != len(key):
3014                     raise ValueError("Columns must be same length as key")
3015                 for k1, k2 in zip(key, value.columns):
3016                     self[k1] = value[k2]
3017             else:
3018                 self.loc._ensure_listlike_indexer(key, axis=1)
3019                 indexer = self.loc._get_listlike_indexer(
3020                     key, axis=1, raise_missing=False
3021                 )[1]
3022                 self._check_setitem_copy()
3023                 self.iloc._setitem_with_indexer((slice(None), indexer), value)
3024 
3025     def _setitem_frame(self, key, value):
3026         # support boolean setting with DataFrame input, e.g.
3027         # df[df > df2] = 0
3028         if isinstance(key, np.ndarray):
3029             if key.shape != self.shape:
3030                 raise ValueError("Array conditional must be same shape as self")
3031             key = self._constructor(key, **self._construct_axes_dict())
3032 
3033         if key.size and not is_bool_dtype(key.values):
3034             raise TypeError(
3035                 "Must pass DataFrame or 2-d ndarray with boolean values only"
3036             )
3037 
3038         self._check_inplace_setting(value)
3039         self._check_setitem_copy()
3040         self._where(-key, value, inplace=True)
3041 
3042     def _iset_item(self, loc: int, value):
3043         self._ensure_valid_index(value)
3044 
3045         # technically _sanitize_column expects a label, not a position,
3046         #  but the behavior is the same as long as we pass broadcast=False
3047         value = self._sanitize_column(loc, value, broadcast=False)
3048         NDFrame._iset_item(self, loc, value)
3049 
3050         # check if we are modifying a copy
3051         # try to set first as we want an invalid
3052         # value exception to occur first
3053         if len(self):
3054             self._check_setitem_copy()
3055 
3056     def _set_item(self, key, value):
3057         """
3058         Add series to DataFrame in specified column.
3059 
3060         If series is a numpy-array (not a Series/TimeSeries), it must be the
3061         same length as the DataFrames index or an error will be thrown.
3062 
3063         Series/TimeSeries will be conformed to the DataFrames index to
3064         ensure homogeneity.
3065         """
3066         self._ensure_valid_index(value)
3067         value = self._sanitize_column(key, value)
3068         NDFrame._set_item(self, key, value)
3069 
3070         # check if we are modifying a copy
3071         # try to set first as we want an invalid
3072         # value exception to occur first
3073         if len(self):
3074             self._check_setitem_copy()
3075 
3076     def _set_value(self, index, col, value, takeable: bool = False):
3077         """
3078         Put single value at passed column and index.
3079 
3080         Parameters
3081         ----------
3082         index : row label
3083         col : column label
3084         value : scalar
3085         takeable : interpret the index/col as indexers, default False
3086         """
3087         try:
3088             if takeable is True:
3089                 series = self._ixs(col, axis=1)
3090                 series._set_value(index, value, takeable=True)
3091                 return
3092 
3093             series = self._get_item_cache(col)
3094             engine = self.index._engine
3095             loc = engine.get_loc(index)
3096             validate_numeric_casting(series.dtype, value)
3097 
3098             series._values[loc] = value
3099             # Note: trying to use series._set_value breaks tests in
3100             #  tests.frame.indexing.test_indexing and tests.indexing.test_partial
3101         except (KeyError, TypeError):
3102             # set using a non-recursive method & reset the cache
3103             if takeable:
3104                 self.iloc[index, col] = value
3105             else:
3106                 self.loc[index, col] = value
3107             self._item_cache.pop(col, None)
3108 
3109     def _ensure_valid_index(self, value):
3110         """
3111         Ensure that if we don't have an index, that we can create one from the
3112         passed value.
3113         """
3114         # GH5632, make sure that we are a Series convertible
3115         if not len(self.index) and is_list_like(value) and len(value):
3116             try:
3117                 value = Series(value)
3118             except (ValueError, NotImplementedError, TypeError) as err:
3119                 raise ValueError(
3120                     "Cannot set a frame with no defined index "
3121                     "and a value that cannot be converted to a Series"
3122                 ) from err
3123 
3124             self._mgr = self._mgr.reindex_axis(
3125                 value.index.copy(), axis=1, fill_value=np.nan
3126             )
3127 
3128     def _box_col_values(self, values, loc: int) -> Series:
3129         """
3130         Provide boxed values for a column.
3131         """
3132         # Lookup in columns so that if e.g. a str datetime was passed
3133         #  we attach the Timestamp object as the name.
3134         name = self.columns[loc]
3135         klass = self._constructor_sliced
3136         return klass(values, index=self.index, name=name, fastpath=True)

3138     # ----------------------------------------------------------------------
3139     # Unsorted
3140 
3141     def query(self, expr, inplace=False, **kwargs):
3142         """
3143         Query the columns of a DataFrame with a boolean expression.
3144 
3145         Parameters
3146         ----------
3147         expr : str
3148             The query string to evaluate.
3149 
3150             You can refer to variables
3151             in the environment by prefixing them with an '@' character like
3152             ``@a + b``.
3153 
3154             You can refer to column names that contain spaces or operators by
3155             surrounding them in backticks. This way you can also escape
3156             names that start with a digit, or those that  are a Python keyword.
3157             Basically when it is not valid Python identifier. See notes down
3158             for more details.
3159 
3160             For example, if one of your columns is called ``a a`` and you want
3161             to sum it with ``b``, your query should be ```a a` + b``.
3162 
3163             .. versionadded:: 0.25.0
3164                 Backtick quoting introduced.
3165 
3166             .. versionadded:: 1.0.0
3167                 Expanding functionality of backtick quoting for more than only spaces.
3168 
3169         inplace : bool
3170             Whether the query should modify the data in place or return
3171             a modified copy.
3172         **kwargs
3173             See the documentation for :func:`eval` for complete details
3174             on the keyword arguments accepted by :meth:`DataFrame.query`.
3175 
3176         Returns
3177         -------
3178         DataFrame
3179             DataFrame resulting from the provided query expression.
3180 
3181         See Also
3182         --------
3183         eval : Evaluate a string describing operations on
3184             DataFrame columns.
3185         DataFrame.eval : Evaluate a string describing operations on
3186             DataFrame columns.
3187 
3188         Notes
3189         -----
3190         The result of the evaluation of this expression is first passed to
3191         :attr:`DataFrame.loc` and if that fails because of a
3192         multidimensional key (e.g., a DataFrame) then the result will be passed
3193         to :meth:`DataFrame.__getitem__`.
3194 
3195         This method uses the top-level :func:`eval` function to
3196         evaluate the passed query.
3197 
3198         The :meth:`~pandas.DataFrame.query` method uses a slightly
3199         modified Python syntax by default. For example, the ``&`` and ``|``
3200         (bitwise) operators have the precedence of their boolean cousins,
3201         :keyword:`and` and :keyword:`or`. This *is* syntactically valid Python,
3202         however the semantics are different.
3203 
3204         You can change the semantics of the expression by passing the keyword
3205         argument ``parser='python'``. This enforces the same semantics as
3206         evaluation in Python space. Likewise, you can pass ``engine='python'``
3207         to evaluate an expression using Python itself as a backend. This is not
3208         recommended as it is inefficient compared to using ``numexpr`` as the
3209         engine.
3210 
3211         The :attr:`DataFrame.index` and
3212         :attr:`DataFrame.columns` attributes of the
3213         :class:`~pandas.DataFrame` instance are placed in the query namespace
3214         by default, which allows you to treat both the index and columns of the
3215         frame as a column in the frame.
3216         The identifier ``index`` is used for the frame index; you can also
3217         use the name of the index to identify it in a query. Please note that
3218         Python keywords may not be used as identifiers.
3219 
3220         For further details and examples see the ``query`` documentation in
3221         :ref:`indexing <indexing.query>`.
3222 
3223         *Backtick quoted variables*
3224 
3225         Backtick quoted variables are parsed as literal Python code and
3226         are converted internally to a Python valid identifier.
3227         This can lead to the following problems.
3228 
3229         During parsing a number of disallowed characters inside the backtick
3230         quoted string are replaced by strings that are allowed as a Python identifier.
3231         These characters include all operators in Python, the space character, the
3232         question mark, the exclamation mark, the dollar sign, and the euro sign.
3233         For other characters that fall outside the ASCII range (U+0001..U+007F)
3234         and those that are not further specified in PEP 3131,
3235         the query parser will raise an error.
3236         This excludes whitespace different than the space character,
3237         but also the hashtag (as it is used for comments) and the backtick
3238         itself (backtick can also not be escaped).
3239 
3240         In a special case, quotes that make a pair around a backtick can
3241         confuse the parser.
3242         For example, ```it's` > `that's``` will raise an error,
3243         as it forms a quoted string (``'s > `that'``) with a backtick inside.
3244 
3245         See also the Python documentation about lexical analysis
3246         (https://docs.python.org/3/reference/lexical_analysis.html)
3247         in combination with the source code in :mod:`pandas.core.computation.parsing`.
3248 
3249         Examples
3250         --------
3251         >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'A': range(1, 6),
3252         ...                    'B': range(10, 0, -2),
3253         ...                    'C C': range(10, 5, -1)})
3254         >>> df
3255            A   B  C C
3256         0  1  10   10
3257         1  2   8    9
3258         2  3   6    8
3259         3  4   4    7
3260         4  5   2    6
3261         >>> df.query('A > B')
3262            A  B  C C
3263         4  5  2    6
3264 
3265         The previous expression is equivalent to
3266 
3267         >>> df[df.A > df.B]
3268            A  B  C C
3269         4  5  2    6
3270 
3271         For columns with spaces in their name, you can use backtick quoting.
3272 
3273         >>> df.query('B == `C C`')
3274            A   B  C C
3275         0  1  10   10
3276 
3277         The previous expression is equivalent to
3278 
3279         >>> df[df.B == df['C C']]
3280            A   B  C C
3281         0  1  10   10
3282         """
3283         inplace = validate_bool_kwarg(inplace, "inplace")
3284         if not isinstance(expr, str):
3285             msg = f"expr must be a string to be evaluated, {type(expr)} given"
3286             raise ValueError(msg)
3287         kwargs["level"] = kwargs.pop("level", 0) + 1
3288         kwargs["target"] = None
3289         res = self.eval(expr, **kwargs)
3290 
3291         try:
3292             result = self.loc[res]
3293         except ValueError:
3294             # when res is multi-dimensional loc raises, but this is sometimes a
3295             # valid query
3296             result = self[res]
3297 
3298         if inplace:
3299             self._update_inplace(result)
3300         else:
3301             return result
3302 
3303     def eval(self, expr, inplace=False, **kwargs):
3304         """
3305         Evaluate a string describing operations on DataFrame columns.
3306 
3307         Operates on columns only, not specific rows or elements.  This allows
3308         `eval` to run arbitrary code, which can make you vulnerable to code
3309         injection if you pass user input to this function.
3310 
3311         Parameters
3312         ----------
3313         expr : str
3314             The expression string to evaluate.
3315         inplace : bool, default False
3316             If the expression contains an assignment, whether to perform the
3317             operation inplace and mutate the existing DataFrame. Otherwise,
3318             a new DataFrame is returned.
3319         **kwargs
3320             See the documentation for :func:`eval` for complete details
3321             on the keyword arguments accepted by
3322             :meth:`~pandas.DataFrame.query`.
3323 
3324         Returns
3325         -------
3326         ndarray, scalar, or pandas object
3327             The result of the evaluation.
3328 
3329         See Also
3330         --------
3331         DataFrame.query : Evaluates a boolean expression to query the columns
3332             of a frame.
3333         DataFrame.assign : Can evaluate an expression or function to create new
3334             values for a column.
3335         eval : Evaluate a Python expression as a string using various
3336             backends.
3337 
3338         Notes
3339         -----
3340         For more details see the API documentation for :func:`~eval`.
3341         For detailed examples see :ref:`enhancing performance with eval
3342         <enhancingperf.eval>`.
3343 
3344         Examples
3345         --------
3346         >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'A': range(1, 6), 'B': range(10, 0, -2)})
3347         >>> df
3348            A   B
3349         0  1  10
3350         1  2   8
3351         2  3   6
3352         3  4   4
3353         4  5   2
3354         >>> df.eval('A + B')
3355         0    11
3356         1    10
3357         2     9
3358         3     8
3359         4     7
3360         dtype: int64
3361 
3362         Assignment is allowed though by default the original DataFrame is not
3363         modified.
3364 
3365         >>> df.eval('C = A + B')
3366            A   B   C
3367         0  1  10  11
3368         1  2   8  10
3369         2  3   6   9
3370         3  4   4   8
3371         4  5   2   7
3372         >>> df
3373            A   B
3374         0  1  10
3375         1  2   8
3376         2  3   6
3377         3  4   4
3378         4  5   2
3379 
3380         Use ``inplace=True`` to modify the original DataFrame.
3381 
3382         >>> df.eval('C = A + B', inplace=True)
3383         >>> df
3384            A   B   C
3385         0  1  10  11
3386         1  2   8  10
3387         2  3   6   9
3388         3  4   4   8
3389         4  5   2   7
3390 
3391         Multiple columns can be assigned to using multi-line expressions:
3392 
3393         >>> df.eval(
3394         ...     '''
3395         ... C = A + B
3396         ... D = A - B
3397         ... '''
3398         ... )
3399            A   B   C  D
3400         0  1  10  11 -9
3401         1  2   8  10 -6
3402         2  3   6   9 -3
3403         3  4   4   8  0
3404         4  5   2   7  3
3405         """
3406         from pandas.core.computation.eval import eval as _eval
3407 
3408         inplace = validate_bool_kwarg(inplace, "inplace")
3409         resolvers = kwargs.pop("resolvers", None)
3410         kwargs["level"] = kwargs.pop("level", 0) + 1
3411         if resolvers is None:
3412             index_resolvers = self._get_index_resolvers()
3413             column_resolvers = self._get_cleaned_column_resolvers()
3414             resolvers = column_resolvers, index_resolvers
3415         if "target" not in kwargs:
3416             kwargs["target"] = self
3417         kwargs["resolvers"] = kwargs.get("resolvers", ()) + tuple(resolvers)
3418 
3419         return _eval(expr, inplace=inplace, **kwargs)
3420 
3421     def select_dtypes(self, include=None, exclude=None) -> "DataFrame":
3422         """
3423         Return a subset of the DataFrame's columns based on the column dtypes.
3424 
3425         Parameters
3426         ----------
3427         include, exclude : scalar or list-like
3428             A selection of dtypes or strings to be included/excluded. At least
3429             one of these parameters must be supplied.
3430 
3431         Returns
3432         -------
3433         DataFrame
3434             The subset of the frame including the dtypes in ``include`` and
3435             excluding the dtypes in ``exclude``.
3436 
3437         Raises
3438         ------
3439         ValueError
3440             * If both of ``include`` and ``exclude`` are empty
3441             * If ``include`` and ``exclude`` have overlapping elements
3442             * If any kind of string dtype is passed in.
3443 
3444         See Also
3445         --------
3446         DataFrame.dtypes: Return Series with the data type of each column.
3447 
3448         Notes
3449         -----
3450         * To select all *numeric* types, use ``np.number`` or ``'number'``
3451         * To select strings you must use the ``object`` dtype, but note that
3452           this will return *all* object dtype columns
3453         * See the `numpy dtype hierarchy
3454           <https://numpy.org/doc/stable/reference/arrays.scalars.html>`__
3455         * To select datetimes, use ``np.datetime64``, ``'datetime'`` or
3456           ``'datetime64'``
3457         * To select timedeltas, use ``np.timedelta64``, ``'timedelta'`` or
3458           ``'timedelta64'``
3459         * To select Pandas categorical dtypes, use ``'category'``
3460         * To select Pandas datetimetz dtypes, use ``'datetimetz'`` (new in
3461           0.20.0) or ``'datetime64[ns, tz]'``
3462 
3463         Examples
3464         --------
3465         >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'a': [1, 2] * 3,
3466         ...                    'b': [True, False] * 3,
3467         ...                    'c': [1.0, 2.0] * 3})
3468         >>> df
3469                 a      b  c
3470         0       1   True  1.0
3471         1       2  False  2.0
3472         2       1   True  1.0
3473         3       2  False  2.0
3474         4       1   True  1.0
3475         5       2  False  2.0
3476 
3477         >>> df.select_dtypes(include='bool')
3478            b
3479         0  True
3480         1  False
3481         2  True
3482         3  False
3483         4  True
3484         5  False
3485 
3486         >>> df.select_dtypes(include=['float64'])
3487            c
3488         0  1.0
3489         1  2.0
3490         2  1.0
3491         3  2.0
3492         4  1.0
3493         5  2.0
3494 
3495         >>> df.select_dtypes(exclude=['int64'])
3496                b    c
3497         0   True  1.0
3498         1  False  2.0
3499         2   True  1.0
3500         3  False  2.0
3501         4   True  1.0
3502         5  False  2.0
3503         """
3504         if not is_list_like(include):
3505             include = (include,) if include is not None else ()
3506         if not is_list_like(exclude):
3507             exclude = (exclude,) if exclude is not None else ()
3508 
3509         selection = (frozenset(include), frozenset(exclude))
3510 
3511         if not any(selection):
3512             raise ValueError("at least one of include or exclude must be nonempty")
3513 
3514         # convert the myriad valid dtypes object to a single representation
3515         include = frozenset(infer_dtype_from_object(x) for x in include)
3516         exclude = frozenset(infer_dtype_from_object(x) for x in exclude)
3517         for dtypes in (include, exclude):
3518             invalidate_string_dtypes(dtypes)
3519 
3520         # can't both include AND exclude!
3521         if not include.isdisjoint(exclude):
3522             raise ValueError(f"include and exclude overlap on {(include & exclude)}")
3523 
3524         # We raise when both include and exclude are empty
3525         # Hence, we can just shrink the columns we want to keep
3526         keep_these = np.full(self.shape[1], True)
3527 
3528         def extract_unique_dtypes_from_dtypes_set(
3529             dtypes_set: FrozenSet[Dtype], unique_dtypes: np.ndarray
3530         ) -> List[Dtype]:
3531             extracted_dtypes = [
3532                 unique_dtype
3533                 for unique_dtype in unique_dtypes
3534                 if issubclass(unique_dtype.type, tuple(dtypes_set))  # type: ignore
3535             ]
3536             return extracted_dtypes
3537 
3538         unique_dtypes = self.dtypes.unique()
3539 
3540         if include:
3541             included_dtypes = extract_unique_dtypes_from_dtypes_set(
3542                 include, unique_dtypes
3543             )
3544             keep_these &= self.dtypes.isin(included_dtypes)
3545 
3546         if exclude:
3547             excluded_dtypes = extract_unique_dtypes_from_dtypes_set(
3548                 exclude, unique_dtypes
3549             )
3550             keep_these &= ~self.dtypes.isin(excluded_dtypes)
3551 
3552         return self.iloc[:, keep_these.values]
3553 
3554     def insert(self, loc, column, value, allow_duplicates=False) -> None:
3555         """
3556         Insert column into DataFrame at specified location.
3557 
3558         Raises a ValueError if `column` is already contained in the DataFrame,
3559         unless `allow_duplicates` is set to True.
3560 
3561         Parameters
3562         ----------
3563         loc : int
3564             Insertion index. Must verify 0 <= loc <= len(columns).
3565         column : str, number, or hashable object
3566             Label of the inserted column.
3567         value : int, Series, or array-like
3568         allow_duplicates : bool, optional
3569         """
3570         self._ensure_valid_index(value)
3571         value = self._sanitize_column(column, value, broadcast=False)
3572         self._mgr.insert(loc, column, value, allow_duplicates=allow_duplicates)
3573 
3574     def assign(self, **kwargs) -> "DataFrame":
3575         r"""
3576         Assign new columns to a DataFrame.
3577 
3578         Returns a new object with all original columns in addition to new ones.
3579         Existing columns that are re-assigned will be overwritten.
3580 
3581         Parameters
3582         ----------
3583         **kwargs : dict of {str: callable or Series}
3584             The column names are keywords. If the values are
3585             callable, they are computed on the DataFrame and
3586             assigned to the new columns. The callable must not
3587             change input DataFrame (though pandas doesn't check it).
3588             If the values are not callable, (e.g. a Series, scalar, or array),
3589             they are simply assigned.
3590 
3591         Returns
3592         -------
3593         DataFrame
3594             A new DataFrame with the new columns in addition to
3595             all the existing columns.
3596 
3597         Notes
3598         -----
3599         Assigning multiple columns within the same ``assign`` is possible.
3600         Later items in '\*\*kwargs' may refer to newly created or modified
3601         columns in 'df'; items are computed and assigned into 'df' in order.
3602 
3603         .. versionchanged:: 0.23.0
3604 
3605            Keyword argument order is maintained.
3606 
3607         Examples
3608         --------
3609         >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'temp_c': [17.0, 25.0]},
3610         ...                   index=['Portland', 'Berkeley'])
3611         >>> df
3612                   temp_c
3613         Portland    17.0
3614         Berkeley    25.0
3615 
3616         Where the value is a callable, evaluated on `df`:
3617 
3618         >>> df.assign(temp_f=lambda x: x.temp_c * 9 / 5 + 32)
3619                   temp_c  temp_f
3620         Portland    17.0    62.6
3621         Berkeley    25.0    77.0
3622 
3623         Alternatively, the same behavior can be achieved by directly
3624         referencing an existing Series or sequence:
3625 
3626         >>> df.assign(temp_f=df['temp_c'] * 9 / 5 + 32)
3627                   temp_c  temp_f
3628         Portland    17.0    62.6
3629         Berkeley    25.0    77.0
3630 
3631         You can create multiple columns within the same assign where one
3632         of the columns depends on another one defined within the same assign:
3633 
3634         >>> df.assign(temp_f=lambda x: x['temp_c'] * 9 / 5 + 32,
3635         ...           temp_k=lambda x: (x['temp_f'] +  459.67) * 5 / 9)
3636                   temp_c  temp_f  temp_k
3637         Portland    17.0    62.6  290.15
3638         Berkeley    25.0    77.0  298.15
3639         """
3640         data = self.copy()
3641 
3642         for k, v in kwargs.items():
3643             data[k] = com.apply_if_callable(v, data)
3644         return data
3645 
3646     def _sanitize_column(self, key, value, broadcast=True):
3647         """
3648         Ensures new columns (which go into the BlockManager as new blocks) are
3649         always copied and converted into an array.
3650 
3651         Parameters
3652         ----------
3653         key : object
3654         value : scalar, Series, or array-like
3655         broadcast : bool, default True
3656             If ``key`` matches multiple duplicate column names in the
3657             DataFrame, this parameter indicates whether ``value`` should be
3658             tiled so that the returned array contains a (duplicated) column for
3659             each occurrence of the key. If False, ``value`` will not be tiled.
3660 
3661         Returns
3662         -------
3663         numpy.ndarray
3664         """
3665 
3666         def reindexer(value):
3667             # reindex if necessary
3668 
3669             if value.index.equals(self.index) or not len(self.index):
3670                 value = value._values.copy()
3671             else:
3672 
3673                 # GH 4107
3674                 try:
3675                     value = value.reindex(self.index)._values
3676                 except ValueError as err:
3677                     # raised in MultiIndex.from_tuples, see test_insert_error_msmgs
3678                     if not value.index.is_unique:
3679                         # duplicate axis
3680                         raise err
3681 
3682                     # other
3683                     raise TypeError(
3684                         "incompatible index of inserted column with frame index"
3685                     ) from err
3686             return value
3687 
3688         if isinstance(value, Series):
3689             value = reindexer(value)
3690 
3691         elif isinstance(value, DataFrame):
3692             # align right-hand-side columns if self.columns
3693             # is multi-index and self[key] is a sub-frame
3694             if isinstance(self.columns, MultiIndex) and key in self.columns:
3695                 loc = self.columns.get_loc(key)
3696                 if isinstance(loc, (slice, Series, np.ndarray, Index)):
3697                     cols = maybe_droplevels(self.columns[loc], key)
3698                     if len(cols) and not cols.equals(value.columns):
3699                         value = value.reindex(cols, axis=1)
3700             # now align rows
3701             value = reindexer(value).T
3702 
3703         elif isinstance(value, ExtensionArray):
3704             # Explicitly copy here, instead of in sanitize_index,
3705             # as sanitize_index won't copy an EA, even with copy=True
3706             value = value.copy()
3707             value = sanitize_index(value, self.index)
3708 
3709         elif isinstance(value, Index) or is_sequence(value):
3710 
3711             # turn me into an ndarray
3712             value = sanitize_index(value, self.index)
3713             if not isinstance(value, (np.ndarray, Index)):
3714                 if isinstance(value, list) and len(value) > 0:
3715                     value = maybe_convert_platform(value)
3716                 else:
3717                     value = com.asarray_tuplesafe(value)
3718             elif value.ndim == 2:
3719                 value = value.copy().T
3720             elif isinstance(value, Index):
3721                 value = value.copy(deep=True)
3722             else:
3723                 value = value.copy()
3724 
3725             # possibly infer to datetimelike
3726             if is_object_dtype(value.dtype):
3727                 value = maybe_infer_to_datetimelike(value)
3728 
3729         else:
3730             # cast ignores pandas dtypes. so save the dtype first
3731             infer_dtype, _ = infer_dtype_from_scalar(value, pandas_dtype=True)
3732 
3733             # upcast
3734             value = cast_scalar_to_array(len(self.index), value)
3735             value = maybe_cast_to_datetime(value, infer_dtype)
3736 
3737         # return internal types directly
3738         if is_extension_array_dtype(value):
3739             return value
3740 
3741         # broadcast across multiple columns if necessary
3742         if broadcast and key in self.columns and value.ndim == 1:
3743             if not self.columns.is_unique or isinstance(self.columns, MultiIndex):
3744                 existing_piece = self[key]
3745                 if isinstance(existing_piece, DataFrame):
3746                     value = np.tile(value, (len(existing_piece.columns), 1))
3747 
3748         return np.atleast_2d(np.asarray(value))
3749 
3750     @property
3751     def _series(self):
3752         return {
3753             item: Series(
3754                 self._mgr.iget(idx), index=self.index, name=item, fastpath=True
3755             )
3756             for idx, item in enumerate(self.columns)
3757         }
3758 
3759     def lookup(self, row_labels, col_labels) -> np.ndarray:
3760         """
3761         Label-based "fancy indexing" function for DataFrame.
3762 
3763         Given equal-length arrays of row and column labels, return an
3764         array of the values corresponding to each (row, col) pair.
3765 
3766         Parameters
3767         ----------
3768         row_labels : sequence
3769             The row labels to use for lookup.
3770         col_labels : sequence
3771             The column labels to use for lookup.
3772 
3773         Returns
3774         -------
3775         numpy.ndarray
3776             The found values.
3777         """
3778         n = len(row_labels)
3779         if n != len(col_labels):
3780             raise ValueError("Row labels must have same size as column labels")
3781         if not (self.index.is_unique and self.columns.is_unique):
3782             # GH#33041
3783             raise ValueError("DataFrame.lookup requires unique index and columns")
3784 
3785         thresh = 1000
3786         if not self._is_mixed_type or n > thresh:
3787             values = self.values
3788             ridx = self.index.get_indexer(row_labels)
3789             cidx = self.columns.get_indexer(col_labels)
3790             if (ridx == -1).any():
3791                 raise KeyError("One or more row labels was not found")
3792             if (cidx == -1).any():
3793                 raise KeyError("One or more column labels was not found")
3794             flat_index = ridx * len(self.columns) + cidx
3795             result = values.flat[flat_index]
3796         else:
3797             result = np.empty(n, dtype="O")
3798             for i, (r, c) in enumerate(zip(row_labels, col_labels)):
3799                 result[i] = self._get_value(r, c)
3800 
3801         if is_object_dtype(result):
3802             result = lib.maybe_convert_objects(result)
3803 
3804         return result
3805 
3806     # ----------------------------------------------------------------------
3807     # Reindexing and alignment
3808 
3809     def _reindex_axes(self, axes, level, limit, tolerance, method, fill_value, copy):
3810         frame = self
3811 
3812         columns = axes["columns"]
3813         if columns is not None:
3814             frame = frame._reindex_columns(
3815                 columns, method, copy, level, fill_value, limit, tolerance
3816             )
3817 
3818         index = axes["index"]
3819         if index is not None:
3820             frame = frame._reindex_index(
3821                 index, method, copy, level, fill_value, limit, tolerance
3822             )
3823 
3824         return frame
3825 
3826     def _reindex_index(
3827         self,
3828         new_index,
3829         method,
3830         copy,
3831         level,
3832         fill_value=np.nan,
3833         limit=None,
3834         tolerance=None,
3835     ):
3836         new_index, indexer = self.index.reindex(
3837             new_index, method=method, level=level, limit=limit, tolerance=tolerance
3838         )
3839         return self._reindex_with_indexers(
3840             {0: [new_index, indexer]},
3841             copy=copy,
3842             fill_value=fill_value,
3843             allow_dups=False,
3844         )
3845 
3846     def _reindex_columns(
3847         self,
3848         new_columns,
3849         method,
3850         copy,
3851         level,
3852         fill_value=None,
3853         limit=None,
3854         tolerance=None,
3855     ):
3856         new_columns, indexer = self.columns.reindex(
3857             new_columns, method=method, level=level, limit=limit, tolerance=tolerance
3858         )
3859         return self._reindex_with_indexers(
3860             {1: [new_columns, indexer]},
3861             copy=copy,
3862             fill_value=fill_value,
3863             allow_dups=False,
3864         )
3865 
3866     def _reindex_multi(self, axes, copy, fill_value) -> "DataFrame":
3867         """
3868         We are guaranteed non-Nones in the axes.
3869         """
3870         new_index, row_indexer = self.index.reindex(axes["index"])
3871         new_columns, col_indexer = self.columns.reindex(axes["columns"])
3872 
3873         if row_indexer is not None and col_indexer is not None:
3874             indexer = row_indexer, col_indexer
3875             new_values = algorithms.take_2d_multi(
3876                 self.values, indexer, fill_value=fill_value
3877             )
3878             return self._constructor(new_values, index=new_index, columns=new_columns)
3879         else:
3880             return self._reindex_with_indexers(
3881                 {0: [new_index, row_indexer], 1: [new_columns, col_indexer]},
3882                 copy=copy,
3883                 fill_value=fill_value,
3884             )
3885 
3886     @doc(NDFrame.align, **_shared_doc_kwargs)
3887     def align(
3888         self,

3890         join="outer",
3891         axis=None,

3893         copy=True,
3894         fill_value=None,
3895         method=None,
3896         limit=None,
3897         fill_axis=0,
3898         broadcast_axis=None,
3899     ) -> "DataFrame":
3900         return super().align(
3901             other,
3902             join=join,
3903             axis=axis,
3904             level=level,
3905             copy=copy,
3906             fill_value=fill_value,
3907             method=method,
3908             limit=limit,
3909             fill_axis=fill_axis,
3910             broadcast_axis=broadcast_axis,
3911         )

3976     def drop(
3977         self,
3978         labels=None,
3979         axis=0,
3980         index=None,
3981         columns=None,
3982         level=None,
3983         inplace=False,
3984         errors="raise",
3985     ):
3986         """
3987         Drop specified labels from rows or columns.
3988 
3989         Remove rows or columns by specifying label names and corresponding
3990         axis, or by specifying directly index or column names. When using a
3991         multi-index, labels on different levels can be removed by specifying
3992         the level.
3993 
3994         Parameters
3995         ----------
3996         labels : single label or list-like
3997             Index or column labels to drop.
3998         axis : {0 or 'index', 1 or 'columns'}, default 0
3999             Whether to drop labels from the index (0 or 'index') or
4000             columns (1 or 'columns').
4001         index : single label or list-like
4002             Alternative to specifying axis (``labels, axis=0``
4003             is equivalent to ``index=labels``).
4004         columns : single label or list-like
4005             Alternative to specifying axis (``labels, axis=1``
4006             is equivalent to ``columns=labels``).
4007         level : int or level name, optional
4008             For MultiIndex, level from which the labels will be removed.
4009         inplace : bool, default False
4010             If True, do operation inplace and return None.
4011         errors : {'ignore', 'raise'}, default 'raise'
4012             If 'ignore', suppress error and only existing labels are
4013             dropped.
4014 
4015         Returns
4016         -------
4017         DataFrame
4018             DataFrame without the removed index or column labels.
4019 
4020         Raises
4021         ------
4022         KeyError
4023             If any of the labels is not found in the selected axis.
4024 
4025         See Also
4026         --------
4027         DataFrame.loc : Label-location based indexer for selection by label.
4028         DataFrame.dropna : Return DataFrame with labels on given axis omitted
4029             where (all or any) data are missing.
4030         DataFrame.drop_duplicates : Return DataFrame with duplicate rows
4031             removed, optionally only considering certain columns.
4032         Series.drop : Return Series with specified index labels removed.
4033 
4034         Examples
4035         --------
4036         >>> df = pd.DataFrame(np.arange(12).reshape(3, 4),
4037         ...                   columns=['A', 'B', 'C', 'D'])
4038         >>> df
4039            A  B   C   D
4040         0  0  1   2   3
4041         1  4  5   6   7
4042         2  8  9  10  11
4043 
4044         Drop columns
4045 
4046         >>> df.drop(['B', 'C'], axis=1)
4047            A   D
4048         0  0   3
4049         1  4   7
4050         2  8  11
4051 
4052         >>> df.drop(columns=['B', 'C'])
4053            A   D
4054         0  0   3
4055         1  4   7
4056         2  8  11
4057 
4058         Drop a row by index
4059 
4060         >>> df.drop([0, 1])
4061            A  B   C   D
4062         2  8  9  10  11
4063 
4064         Drop columns and/or rows of MultiIndex DataFrame
4065 
4066         >>> midx = pd.MultiIndex(levels=[['lama', 'cow', 'falcon'],
4067         ...                              ['speed', 'weight', 'length']],
4068         ...                      codes=[[0, 0, 0, 1, 1, 1, 2, 2, 2],
4069         ...                             [0, 1, 2, 0, 1, 2, 0, 1, 2]])
4070         >>> df = pd.DataFrame(index=midx, columns=['big', 'small'],
4071         ...                   data=[[45, 30], [200, 100], [1.5, 1], [30, 20],
4072         ...                         [250, 150], [1.5, 0.8], [320, 250],
4073         ...                         [1, 0.8], [0.3, 0.2]])
4074         >>> df
4075                         big     small
4076         lama    speed   45.0    30.0
4077                 weight  200.0   100.0
4078                 length  1.5     1.0
4079         cow     speed   30.0    20.0
4080                 weight  250.0   150.0
4081                 length  1.5     0.8
4082         falcon  speed   320.0   250.0
4083                 weight  1.0     0.8
4084                 length  0.3     0.2
4085 
4086         >>> df.drop(index='cow', columns='small')
4087                         big
4088         lama    speed   45.0
4089                 weight  200.0
4090                 length  1.5
4091         falcon  speed   320.0
4092                 weight  1.0
4093                 length  0.3
4094 
4095         >>> df.drop(index='length', level=1)
4096                         big     small
4097         lama    speed   45.0    30.0
4098                 weight  200.0   100.0
4099         cow     speed   30.0    20.0
4100                 weight  250.0   150.0
4101         falcon  speed   320.0   250.0
4102                 weight  1.0     0.8
4103         """
4104         return super().drop(
4105             labels=labels,
4106             axis=axis,
4107             index=index,
4108             columns=columns,
4109             level=level,
4110             inplace=inplace,
4111             errors=errors,
4112         )

4114     @rewrite_axis_style_signature(
4115         "mapper",
4116         [("copy", True), ("inplace", False), ("level", None), ("errors", "ignore")],
4117     )
4118     def rename(
4119         self,
4120         mapper: Optional[Renamer] = None,
4121         *,
4122         index: Optional[Renamer] = None,
4123         columns: Optional[Renamer] = None,
4124         axis: Optional[Axis] = None,
4125         copy: bool = True,
4126         inplace: bool = False,
4127         level: Optional[Level] = None,
4128         errors: str = "ignore",
4129     ) -> Optional["DataFrame"]:
4130         """
4131         Alter axes labels.
4132 
4133         Function / dict values must be unique (1-to-1). Labels not contained in
4134         a dict / Series will be left as-is. Extra labels listed don't throw an
4135         error.
4136 
4137         See the :ref:`user guide <basics.rename>` for more.
4138 
4139         Parameters
4140         ----------
4141         mapper : dict-like or function
4142             Dict-like or functions transformations to apply to
4143             that axis' values. Use either ``mapper`` and ``axis`` to
4144             specify the axis to target with ``mapper``, or ``index`` and
4145             ``columns``.
4146         index : dict-like or function
4147             Alternative to specifying axis (``mapper, axis=0``
4148             is equivalent to ``index=mapper``).
4149         columns : dict-like or function
4150             Alternative to specifying axis (``mapper, axis=1``
4151             is equivalent to ``columns=mapper``).
4152         axis : {0 or 'index', 1 or 'columns'}, default 0
4153             Axis to target with ``mapper``. Can be either the axis name
4154             ('index', 'columns') or number (0, 1). The default is 'index'.
4155         copy : bool, default True
4156             Also copy underlying data.
4157         inplace : bool, default False
4158             Whether to return a new DataFrame. If True then value of copy is
4159             ignored.
4160         level : int or level name, default None
4161             In case of a MultiIndex, only rename labels in the specified
4162             level.
4163         errors : {'ignore', 'raise'}, default 'ignore'
4164             If 'raise', raise a `KeyError` when a dict-like `mapper`, `index`,
4165             or `columns` contains labels that are not present in the Index
4166             being transformed.
4167             If 'ignore', existing keys will be renamed and extra keys will be
4168             ignored.
4169 
4170         Returns
4171         -------
4172         DataFrame
4173             DataFrame with the renamed axis labels.
4174 
4175         Raises
4176         ------
4177         KeyError
4178             If any of the labels is not found in the selected axis and
4179             "errors='raise'".
4180 
4181         See Also
4182         --------
4183         DataFrame.rename_axis : Set the name of the axis.
4184 
4185         Examples
4186         --------
4187         ``DataFrame.rename`` supports two calling conventions
4188 
4189         * ``(index=index_mapper, columns=columns_mapper, ...)``
4190         * ``(mapper, axis={'index', 'columns'}, ...)``
4191 
4192         We *highly* recommend using keyword arguments to clarify your
4193         intent.
4194 
4195         Rename columns using a mapping:
4196 
4197         >>> df = pd.DataFrame({"A": [1, 2, 3], "B": [4, 5, 6]})
4198         >>> df.rename(columns={"A": "a", "B": "c"})
4199            a  c
4200         0  1  4
4201         1  2  5
4202         2  3  6
4203 
4204         Rename index using a mapping:
4205 
4206         >>> df.rename(index={0: "x", 1: "y", 2: "z"})
4207            A  B
4208         x  1  4
4209         y  2  5
4210         z  3  6
4211 
4212         Cast index labels to a different type:
4213 
4214         >>> df.index
4215         RangeIndex(start=0, stop=3, step=1)
4216         >>> df.rename(index=str).index
4217         Index(['0', '1', '2'], dtype='object')
4218 
4219         >>> df.rename(columns={"A": "a", "B": "b", "C": "c"}, errors="raise")
4220         Traceback (most recent call last):
4221         KeyError: ['C'] not found in axis
4222 
4223         Using axis-style parameters
4224 
4225         >>> df.rename(str.lower, axis='columns')
4226            a  b
4227         0  1  4
4228         1  2  5
4229         2  3  6
4230 
4231         >>> df.rename({1: 2, 2: 4}, axis='index')
4232            A  B
4233         0  1  4
4234         2  2  5
4235         4  3  6
4236         """
4237         return super().rename(
4238             mapper=mapper,
4239             index=index,
4240             columns=columns,
4241             axis=axis,
4242             copy=copy,
4243             inplace=inplace,
4244             level=level,
4245             errors=errors,
4246         )
4247

4286     def _replace_columnwise(
4287         self, mapping: Dict[Label, Tuple[Any, Any]], inplace: bool, regex
4288     ):
4289         """
4290         Dispatch to Series.replace column-wise.
4291 
4292 
4293         Parameters
4294         ----------
4295         mapping : dict
4296             of the form {col: (target, value)}
4297         inplace : bool
4298         regex : bool or same types as `to_replace` in DataFrame.replace
4299 
4300         Returns
4301         -------
4302         DataFrame or None
4303         """
4304         # Operate column-wise
4305         res = self if inplace else self.copy()
4306         ax = self.columns
4307 
4308         for i in range(len(ax)):
4309             if ax[i] in mapping:
4310                 ser = self.iloc[:, i]
4311 
4312                 target, value = mapping[ax[i]]
4313                 newobj = ser.replace(target, value, regex=regex)
4314 
4315                 res.iloc[:, i] = newobj
4316 
4317         if inplace:
4318             return
4319         return res.__finalize__(self)
4320

4323         return super().shift(
4324             periods=periods, freq=freq, axis=axis, fill_value=fill_value
4325         )

4327     def set_index(
4328         self, keys, drop=True, append=False, inplace=False, verify_integrity=False
4329     ):
4330         """
4331         Set the DataFrame index using existing columns.
4332 
4333         Set the DataFrame index (row labels) using one or more existing
4334         columns or arrays (of the correct length). The index can replace the
4335         existing index or expand on it.
4336 
4337         Parameters
4338         ----------
4339         keys : label or array-like or list of labels/arrays
4340             This parameter can be either a single column key, a single array of
4341             the same length as the calling DataFrame, or a list containing an
4342             arbitrary combination of column keys and arrays. Here, "array"
4343             encompasses :class:`Series`, :class:`Index`, ``np.ndarray``, and
4344             instances of :class:`~collections.abc.Iterator`.
4345         drop : bool, default True
4346             Delete columns to be used as the new index.
4347         append : bool, default False
4348             Whether to append columns to existing index.
4349         inplace : bool, default False
4350             Modify the DataFrame in place (do not create a new object).
4351         verify_integrity : bool, default False
4352             Check the new index for duplicates. Otherwise defer the check until
4353             necessary. Setting to False will improve the performance of this
4354             method.
4355 
4356         Returns
4357         -------
4358         DataFrame
4359             Changed row labels.
4360 
4361         See Also
4362         --------
4363         DataFrame.reset_index : Opposite of set_index.
4364         DataFrame.reindex : Change to new indices or expand indices.
4365         DataFrame.reindex_like : Change to same indices as other DataFrame.
4366 
4367         Examples
4368         --------
4369         >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'month': [1, 4, 7, 10],
4370         ...                    'year': [2012, 2014, 2013, 2014],
4371         ...                    'sale': [55, 40, 84, 31]})
4372         >>> df
4373            month  year  sale
4374         0      1  2012    55
4375         1      4  2014    40
4376         2      7  2013    84
4377         3     10  2014    31
4378 
4379         Set the index to become the 'month' column:
4380 
4381         >>> df.set_index('month')
4382                year  sale
4383         month
4384         1      2012    55
4385         4      2014    40
4386         7      2013    84
4387         10     2014    31
4388 
4389         Create a MultiIndex using columns 'year' and 'month':
4390 
4391         >>> df.set_index(['year', 'month'])
4392                     sale
4393         year  month
4394         2012  1     55
4395         2014  4     40
4396         2013  7     84
4397         2014  10    31
4398 
4399         Create a MultiIndex using an Index and a column:
4400 
4401         >>> df.set_index([pd.Index([1, 2, 3, 4]), 'year'])
4402                  month  sale
4403            year
4404         1  2012  1      55
4405         2  2014  4      40
4406         3  2013  7      84
4407         4  2014  10     31
4408 
4409         Create a MultiIndex using two Series:
4410 
4411         >>> s = pd.Series([1, 2, 3, 4])
4412         >>> df.set_index([s, s**2])
4413               month  year  sale
4414         1 1       1  2012    55
4415         2 4       4  2014    40
4416         3 9       7  2013    84
4417         4 16     10  2014    31
4418         """
4419         inplace = validate_bool_kwarg(inplace, "inplace")
4420         if not isinstance(keys, list):
4421             keys = [keys]
4422 
4423         err_msg = (
4424             'The parameter "keys" may be a column key, one-dimensional '
4425             "array, or a list containing only valid column keys and "
4426             "one-dimensional arrays."
4427         )
4428 
4429         missing: List[Label] = []
4430         for col in keys:
4431             if isinstance(col, (Index, Series, np.ndarray, list, abc.Iterator)):
4432                 # arrays are fine as long as they are one-dimensional
4433                 # iterators get converted to list below
4434                 if getattr(col, "ndim", 1) != 1:
4435                     raise ValueError(err_msg)
4436             else:
4437                 # everything else gets tried as a key; see GH 24969
4438                 try:
4439                     found = col in self.columns
4440                 except TypeError as err:
4441                     raise TypeError(
4442                         f"{err_msg}. Received column of type {type(col)}"
4443                     ) from err
4444                 else:
4445                     if not found:
4446                         missing.append(col)
4447 
4448         if missing:
4449             raise KeyError(f"None of {missing} are in the columns")
4450 
4451         if inplace:
4452             frame = self
4453         else:
4454             frame = self.copy()
4455 
4456         arrays = []
4457         names = []
4458         if append:
4459             names = list(self.index.names)
4460             if isinstance(self.index, MultiIndex):
4461                 for i in range(self.index.nlevels):
4462                     arrays.append(self.index._get_level_values(i))
4463             else:
4464                 arrays.append(self.index)
4465 
4466         to_remove: List[Label] = []
4467         for col in keys:
4468             if isinstance(col, MultiIndex):
4469                 for n in range(col.nlevels):
4470                     arrays.append(col._get_level_values(n))
4471                 names.extend(col.names)
4472             elif isinstance(col, (Index, Series)):
4473                 # if Index then not MultiIndex (treated above)
4474                 arrays.append(col)
4475                 names.append(col.name)
4476             elif isinstance(col, (list, np.ndarray)):
4477                 arrays.append(col)
4478                 names.append(None)
4479             elif isinstance(col, abc.Iterator):
4480                 arrays.append(list(col))
4481                 names.append(None)
4482             # from here, col can only be a column label
4483             else:
4484                 arrays.append(frame[col]._values)
4485                 names.append(col)
4486                 if drop:
4487                     to_remove.append(col)
4488 
4489             if len(arrays[-1]) != len(self):
4490                 # check newest element against length of calling frame, since
4491                 # ensure_index_from_sequences would not raise for append=False.
4492                 raise ValueError(
4493                     f"Length mismatch: Expected {len(self)} rows, "
4494                     f"received array of length {len(arrays[-1])}"
4495                 )
4496 
4497         index = ensure_index_from_sequences(arrays, names)
4498 
4499         if verify_integrity and not index.is_unique:
4500             duplicates = index[index.duplicated()].unique()
4501             raise ValueError(f"Index has duplicate keys: {duplicates}")
4502 
4503         # use set to handle duplicate column names gracefully in case of drop
4504         for c in set(to_remove):
4505             del frame[c]
4506 
4507         # clear up memory usage
4508         index._cleanup()
4509 
4510         frame.index = index
4511 
4512         if not inplace:
4513             return frame
4514 
4515     def reset_index(
4516         self,
4517         level: Optional[Union[Hashable, Sequence[Hashable]]] = None,
4518         drop: bool = False,
4519         inplace: bool = False,
4520         col_level: Hashable = 0,
4521         col_fill: Label = "",
4522     ) -> Optional["DataFrame"]:
4523         """
4524         Reset the index, or a level of it.
4525 
4526         Reset the index of the DataFrame, and use the default one instead.
4527         If the DataFrame has a MultiIndex, this method can remove one or more
4528         levels.
4529 
4530         Parameters
4531         ----------
4532         level : int, str, tuple, or list, default None
4533             Only remove the given levels from the index. Removes all levels by
4534             default.
4535         drop : bool, default False
4536             Do not try to insert index into dataframe columns. This resets
4537             the index to the default integer index.
4538         inplace : bool, default False
4539             Modify the DataFrame in place (do not create a new object).
4540         col_level : int or str, default 0
4541             If the columns have multiple levels, determines which level the
4542             labels are inserted into. By default it is inserted into the first
4543             level.
4544         col_fill : object, default ''
4545             If the columns have multiple levels, determines how the other
4546             levels are named. If None then the index name is repeated.
4547 
4548         Returns
4549         -------
4550         DataFrame or None
4551             DataFrame with the new index or None if ``inplace=True``.
4552 
4553         See Also
4554         --------
4555         DataFrame.set_index : Opposite of reset_index.
4556         DataFrame.reindex : Change to new indices or expand indices.
4557         DataFrame.reindex_like : Change to same indices as other DataFrame.
4558 
4559         Examples
4560         --------
4561         >>> df = pd.DataFrame([('bird', 389.0),
4562         ...                    ('bird', 24.0),
4563         ...                    ('mammal', 80.5),
4564         ...                    ('mammal', np.nan)],
4565         ...                   index=['falcon', 'parrot', 'lion', 'monkey'],
4566         ...                   columns=('class', 'max_speed'))
4567         >>> df
4568                  class  max_speed
4569         falcon    bird      389.0
4570         parrot    bird       24.0
4571         lion    mammal       80.5
4572         monkey  mammal        NaN
4573 
4574         When we reset the index, the old index is added as a column, and a
4575         new sequential index is used:
4576 
4577         >>> df.reset_index()
4578             index   class  max_speed
4579         0  falcon    bird      389.0
4580         1  parrot    bird       24.0
4581         2    lion  mammal       80.5
4582         3  monkey  mammal        NaN
4583 
4584         We can use the `drop` parameter to avoid the old index being added as
4585         a column:
4586 
4587         >>> df.reset_index(drop=True)
4588             class  max_speed
4589         0    bird      389.0
4590         1    bird       24.0
4591         2  mammal       80.5
4592         3  mammal        NaN
4593 
4594         You can also use `reset_index` with `MultiIndex`.
4595 
4596         >>> index = pd.MultiIndex.from_tuples([('bird', 'falcon'),
4597         ...                                    ('bird', 'parrot'),
4598         ...                                    ('mammal', 'lion'),
4599         ...                                    ('mammal', 'monkey')],
4600         ...                                   names=['class', 'name'])
4601         >>> columns = pd.MultiIndex.from_tuples([('speed', 'max'),
4602         ...                                      ('species', 'type')])
4603         >>> df = pd.DataFrame([(389.0, 'fly'),
4604         ...                    ( 24.0, 'fly'),
4605         ...                    ( 80.5, 'run'),
4606         ...                    (np.nan, 'jump')],
4607         ...                   index=index,
4608         ...                   columns=columns)
4609         >>> df
4610                        speed species
4611                          max    type
4612         class  name
4613         bird   falcon  389.0     fly
4614                parrot   24.0     fly
4615         mammal lion     80.5     run
4616                monkey    NaN    jump
4617 
4618         If the index has multiple levels, we can reset a subset of them:
4619 
4620         >>> df.reset_index(level='class')
4621                  class  speed species
4622                           max    type
4623         name
4624         falcon    bird  389.0     fly
4625         parrot    bird   24.0     fly
4626         lion    mammal   80.5     run
4627         monkey  mammal    NaN    jump
4628 
4629         If we are not dropping the index, by default, it is placed in the top
4630         level. We can place it in another level:
4631 
4632         >>> df.reset_index(level='class', col_level=1)
4633                         speed species
4634                  class    max    type
4635         name
4636         falcon    bird  389.0     fly
4637         parrot    bird   24.0     fly
4638         lion    mammal   80.5     run
4639         monkey  mammal    NaN    jump
4640 
4641         When the index is inserted under another level, we can specify under
4642         which one with the parameter `col_fill`:
4643 
4644         >>> df.reset_index(level='class', col_level=1, col_fill='species')
4645                       species  speed species
4646                         class    max    type
4647         name
4648         falcon           bird  389.0     fly
4649         parrot           bird   24.0     fly
4650         lion           mammal   80.5     run
4651         monkey         mammal    NaN    jump
4652 
4653         If we specify a nonexistent level for `col_fill`, it is created:
4654 
4655         >>> df.reset_index(level='class', col_level=1, col_fill='genus')
4656                         genus  speed species
4657                         class    max    type
4658         name
4659         falcon           bird  389.0     fly
4660         parrot           bird   24.0     fly
