6570     _shared_docs[
6571         "pivot_table"
6572     ] = """
6573         Create a spreadsheet-style pivot table as a DataFrame.
6574 
6575         The levels in the pivot table will be stored in MultiIndex objects
6576         (hierarchical indexes) on the index and columns of the result DataFrame.
6577 
6578         Parameters
6579         ----------%s
6580         values : column to aggregate, optional
6581         index : column, Grouper, array, or list of the previous
6582             If an array is passed, it must be the same length as the data. The
6583             list can contain any of the other types (except list).
6584             Keys to group by on the pivot table index.  If an array is passed,
6585             it is being used as the same manner as column values.
6586         columns : column, Grouper, array, or list of the previous
6587             If an array is passed, it must be the same length as the data. The
6588             list can contain any of the other types (except list).
6589             Keys to group by on the pivot table column.  If an array is passed,
6590             it is being used as the same manner as column values.
6591         aggfunc : function, list of functions, dict, default numpy.mean
6592             If list of functions passed, the resulting pivot table will have
6593             hierarchical columns whose top level are the function names
6594             (inferred from the function objects themselves)
6595             If dict is passed, the key is column to aggregate and value
6596             is function or list of functions.
6597         fill_value : scalar, default None
6598             Value to replace missing values with (in the resulting pivot table,
6599             after aggregation).
6600         margins : bool, default False
6601             Add all row / columns (e.g. for subtotal / grand totals).
6602         dropna : bool, default True
6603             Do not include columns whose entries are all NaN.
6604         margins_name : str, default 'All'
6605             Name of the row / column that will contain the totals
6606             when margins is True.
6607         observed : bool, default False
6608             This only applies if any of the groupers are Categoricals.
6609             If True: only show observed values for categorical groupers.
6610             If False: show all values for categorical groupers.
6611 
6612             .. versionchanged:: 0.25.0
6613 
6614         Returns
6615         -------
6616         DataFrame
6617             An Excel style pivot table.
6618 
6619         See Also
6620         --------
6621         DataFrame.pivot : Pivot without aggregation that can handle
6622             non-numeric data.
6623 
6624         Examples
6625         --------
6626         >>> df = pd.DataFrame({"A": ["foo", "foo", "foo", "foo", "foo",
6627         ...                          "bar", "bar", "bar", "bar"],
6628         ...                    "B": ["one", "one", "one", "two", "two",
6629         ...                          "one", "one", "two", "two"],
6630         ...                    "C": ["small", "large", "large", "small",
6631         ...                          "small", "large", "small", "small",
6632         ...                          "large"],
6633         ...                    "D": [1, 2, 2, 3, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7],
6634         ...                    "E": [2, 4, 5, 5, 6, 6, 8, 9, 9]})
6635         >>> df
6636              A    B      C  D  E
6637         0  foo  one  small  1  2
6638         1  foo  one  large  2  4
6639         2  foo  one  large  2  5
6640         3  foo  two  small  3  5
6641         4  foo  two  small  3  6
6642         5  bar  one  large  4  6
6643         6  bar  one  small  5  8
6644         7  bar  two  small  6  9
6645         8  bar  two  large  7  9
6646 
6647         This first example aggregates values by taking the sum.
6648 
6649         >>> table = pd.pivot_table(df, values='D', index=['A', 'B'],
6650         ...                     columns=['C'], aggfunc=np.sum)
6651         >>> table
6652         C        large  small
6653         A   B
6654         bar one    4.0    5.0
6655             two    7.0    6.0
6656         foo one    4.0    1.0
6657             two    NaN    6.0
6658 
6659         We can also fill missing values using the `fill_value` parameter.
6660 
6661         >>> table = pd.pivot_table(df, values='D', index=['A', 'B'],
6662         ...                     columns=['C'], aggfunc=np.sum, fill_value=0)
6663         >>> table
6664         C        large  small
6665         A   B
6666         bar one      4      5
6667             two      7      6
6668         foo one      4      1
6669             two      0      6
6670 
6671         The next example aggregates by taking the mean across multiple columns.
6672 
6673         >>> table = pd.pivot_table(df, values=['D', 'E'], index=['A', 'C'],
6674         ...                     aggfunc={'D': np.mean,
6675         ...                              'E': np.mean})
6676         >>> table
6677                         D         E
6678         A   C
6679         bar large  5.500000  7.500000
6680             small  5.500000  8.500000
6681         foo large  2.000000  4.500000
6682             small  2.333333  4.333333
6683 
6684         We can also calculate multiple types of aggregations for any given
6685         value column.
6686 
6687         >>> table = pd.pivot_table(df, values=['D', 'E'], index=['A', 'C'],
6688         ...                     aggfunc={'D': np.mean,
6689         ...                              'E': [min, max, np.mean]})
6690         >>> table
6691                         D    E
6692                     mean  max      mean  min
6693         A   C
6694         bar large  5.500000  9.0  7.500000  6.0
6695             small  5.500000  9.0  8.500000  8.0
6696         foo large  2.000000  5.0  4.500000  4.0
6697             small  2.333333  6.0  4.333333  2.0
6698         """
6699 
6700     @Substitution("")
6701     @Appender(_shared_docs["pivot_table"])
6702     def pivot_table(
6703         self,
6704         values=None,
6705         index=None,
6706         columns=None,
6707         aggfunc="mean",
6708         fill_value=None,
6709         margins=False,
6710         dropna=True,
6711         margins_name="All",
6712         observed=False,
6713     ) -> "DataFrame":
6714         from pandas.core.reshape.pivot import pivot_table
6715 
6716         return pivot_table(
6717             self,
6718             values=values,
6719             index=index,
6720             columns=columns,
6721             aggfunc=aggfunc,
6722             fill_value=fill_value,
6723             margins=margins,
6724             dropna=dropna,
6725             margins_name=margins_name,
6726             observed=observed,

6729     def stack(self, level=-1, dropna=True):
6730         """
6731         Stack the prescribed level(s) from columns to index.
6732 
6733         Return a reshaped DataFrame or Series having a multi-level
6734         index with one or more new inner-most levels compared to the current
6735         DataFrame. The new inner-most levels are created by pivoting the
6736         columns of the current dataframe:
6737 
6738           - if the columns have a single level, the output is a Series;
6739           - if the columns have multiple levels, the new index
6740             level(s) is (are) taken from the prescribed level(s) and
6741             the output is a DataFrame.
6742 
6743         The new index levels are sorted.
6744 
6745         Parameters
6746         ----------
6747         level : int, str, list, default -1
6748             Level(s) to stack from the column axis onto the index
6749             axis, defined as one index or label, or a list of indices
6750             or labels.
6751         dropna : bool, default True
6752             Whether to drop rows in the resulting Frame/Series with
6753             missing values. Stacking a column level onto the index
6754             axis can create combinations of index and column values
6755             that are missing from the original dataframe. See Examples
6756             section.
6757 
6758         Returns
6759         -------
6760         DataFrame or Series
6761             Stacked dataframe or series.
6762 
6763         See Also
6764         --------
6765         DataFrame.unstack : Unstack prescribed level(s) from index axis
6766              onto column axis.
6767         DataFrame.pivot : Reshape dataframe from long format to wide
6768              format.
6769         DataFrame.pivot_table : Create a spreadsheet-style pivot table
6770              as a DataFrame.
6771 
6772         Notes
6773         -----
6774         The function is named by analogy with a collection of books
6775         being reorganized from being side by side on a horizontal
6776         position (the columns of the dataframe) to being stacked
6777         vertically on top of each other (in the index of the
6778         dataframe).
6779 
6780         Examples
6781         --------
6782         **Single level columns**
6783 
6784         >>> df_single_level_cols = pd.DataFrame([[0, 1], [2, 3]],
6785         ...                                     index=['cat', 'dog'],
6786         ...                                     columns=['weight', 'height'])
6787 
6788         Stacking a dataframe with a single level column axis returns a Series:
6789 
6790         >>> df_single_level_cols
6791              weight height
6792         cat       0      1
6793         dog       2      3
6794         >>> df_single_level_cols.stack()
6795         cat  weight    0
6796              height    1
6797         dog  weight    2
6798              height    3
6799         dtype: int64
6800 
6801         **Multi level columns: simple case**
6802 
6803         >>> multicol1 = pd.MultiIndex.from_tuples([('weight', 'kg'),
6804         ...                                        ('weight', 'pounds')])
6805         >>> df_multi_level_cols1 = pd.DataFrame([[1, 2], [2, 4]],
6806         ...                                     index=['cat', 'dog'],
6807         ...                                     columns=multicol1)
6808 
6809         Stacking a dataframe with a multi-level column axis:
6810 
6811         >>> df_multi_level_cols1
6812              weight
6813                  kg    pounds
6814         cat       1        2
6815         dog       2        4
6816         >>> df_multi_level_cols1.stack()
6817                     weight
6818         cat kg           1
6819             pounds       2
6820         dog kg           2
6821             pounds       4
6822 
6823         **Missing values**
6824 
6825         >>> multicol2 = pd.MultiIndex.from_tuples([('weight', 'kg'),
6826         ...                                        ('height', 'm')])
6827         >>> df_multi_level_cols2 = pd.DataFrame([[1.0, 2.0], [3.0, 4.0]],
6828         ...                                     index=['cat', 'dog'],
6829         ...                                     columns=multicol2)
6830 
6831         It is common to have missing values when stacking a dataframe
6832         with multi-level columns, as the stacked dataframe typically
6833         has more values than the original dataframe. Missing values
6834         are filled with NaNs:
6835 
6836         >>> df_multi_level_cols2
6837             weight height
6838                 kg      m
6839         cat    1.0    2.0
6840         dog    3.0    4.0
6841         >>> df_multi_level_cols2.stack()
6842                 height  weight
6843         cat kg     NaN     1.0
6844             m      2.0     NaN
6845         dog kg     NaN     3.0
6846             m      4.0     NaN
6847 
6848         **Prescribing the level(s) to be stacked**
6849 
6850         The first parameter controls which level or levels are stacked:
6851 
6852         >>> df_multi_level_cols2.stack(0)
6853                      kg    m
6854         cat height  NaN  2.0
6855             weight  1.0  NaN
6856         dog height  NaN  4.0
6857             weight  3.0  NaN
6858         >>> df_multi_level_cols2.stack([0, 1])
6859         cat  height  m     2.0
6860              weight  kg    1.0
6861         dog  height  m     4.0
6862              weight  kg    3.0
6863         dtype: float64
6864 
6865         **Dropping missing values**
6866 
6867         >>> df_multi_level_cols3 = pd.DataFrame([[None, 1.0], [2.0, 3.0]],
6868         ...                                     index=['cat', 'dog'],
6869         ...                                     columns=multicol2)
6870 
6871         Note that rows where all values are missing are dropped by
6872         default but this behaviour can be controlled via the dropna
6873         keyword parameter:
6874 
6875         >>> df_multi_level_cols3
6876             weight height
6877                 kg      m
6878         cat    NaN    1.0
6879         dog    2.0    3.0
6880         >>> df_multi_level_cols3.stack(dropna=False)
6881                 height  weight
6882         cat kg     NaN     NaN
6883             m      1.0     NaN
6884         dog kg     NaN     2.0
6885             m      3.0     NaN
6886         >>> df_multi_level_cols3.stack(dropna=True)
6887                 height  weight
6888         cat m      1.0     NaN
6889         dog kg     NaN     2.0
6890             m      3.0     NaN
6891         """
6892         from pandas.core.reshape.reshape import stack, stack_multiple
6893 
6894         if isinstance(level, (tuple, list)):
6895             return stack_multiple(self, level, dropna=dropna)
6896         else:
6897             return stack(self, level, dropna=dropna)
6898 
6899     def explode(self, column: Union[str, Tuple]) -> "DataFrame":
6900         """
6901         Transform each element of a list-like to a row, replicating index values.
6902 
6903         .. versionadded:: 0.25.0
6904 
6905         Parameters
6906         ----------
6907         column : str or tuple
6908             Column to explode.
6909 
6910         Returns
6911         -------
6912         DataFrame
6913             Exploded lists to rows of the subset columns;
6914             index will be duplicated for these rows.
6915 
6916         Raises
6917         ------
6918         ValueError :
6919             if columns of the frame are not unique.
6920 
6921         See Also
6922         --------
6923         DataFrame.unstack : Pivot a level of the (necessarily hierarchical)
6924             index labels.
6925         DataFrame.melt : Unpivot a DataFrame from wide format to long format.
6926         Series.explode : Explode a DataFrame from list-like columns to long format.
6927 
6928         Notes
6929         -----
6930         This routine will explode list-likes including lists, tuples,
6931         Series, and np.ndarray. The result dtype of the subset rows will
6932         be object. Scalars will be returned unchanged. Empty list-likes will
6933         result in a np.nan for that row.
6934 
6935         Examples
6936         --------
6937         >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'A': [[1, 2, 3], 'foo', [], [3, 4]], 'B': 1})
6938         >>> df
6939                    A  B
6940         0  [1, 2, 3]  1
6941         1        foo  1
6942         2         []  1
6943         3     [3, 4]  1
6944 
6945         >>> df.explode('A')
6946              A  B
6947         0    1  1
6948         0    2  1
6949         0    3  1
6950         1  foo  1
6951         2  NaN  1
6952         3    3  1
6953         3    4  1
6954         """
6955         if not (is_scalar(column) or isinstance(column, tuple)):
6956             raise ValueError("column must be a scalar")
6957         if not self.columns.is_unique:
6958             raise ValueError("columns must be unique")
6959 
6960         df = self.reset_index(drop=True)
6961         # TODO: use overload to refine return type of reset_index
6962         assert df is not None  # needed for mypy
6963         result = df[column].explode()
6964         result = df.drop([column], axis=1).join(result)
6965         result.index = self.index.take(result.index)
6966         result = result.reindex(columns=self.columns, copy=False)
6967 
6968         return result
6969 
6970     def unstack(self, level=-1, fill_value=None):
6971         """
6972         Pivot a level of the (necessarily hierarchical) index labels.
6973 
6974         Returns a DataFrame having a new level of column labels whose inner-most level
6975         consists of the pivoted index labels.
6976 
6977         If the index is not a MultiIndex, the output will be a Series
6978         (the analogue of stack when the columns are not a MultiIndex).
6979 
6980         The level involved will automatically get sorted.
6981 
6982         Parameters
6983         ----------
6984         level : int, str, or list of these, default -1 (last level)
6985             Level(s) of index to unstack, can pass level name.
6986         fill_value : int, str or dict
6987             Replace NaN with this value if the unstack produces missing values.
6988 
6989         Returns
6990         -------
6991         Series or DataFrame
6992 
6993         See Also
6994         --------
6995         DataFrame.pivot : Pivot a table based on column values.
6996         DataFrame.stack : Pivot a level of the column labels (inverse operation
6997             from `unstack`).
6998 
6999         Examples
7000         --------
7001         >>> index = pd.MultiIndex.from_tuples([('one', 'a'), ('one', 'b'),
7002         ...                                    ('two', 'a'), ('two', 'b')])
7003         >>> s = pd.Series(np.arange(1.0, 5.0), index=index)
7004         >>> s
7005         one  a   1.0
7006              b   2.0
7007         two  a   3.0
7008              b   4.0
7009         dtype: float64
7010 
7011         >>> s.unstack(level=-1)
7012              a   b
7013         one  1.0  2.0
7014         two  3.0  4.0
7015 
7016         >>> s.unstack(level=0)
7017            one  two
7018         a  1.0   3.0
7019         b  2.0   4.0
7020 
7021         >>> df = s.unstack(level=0)
7022         >>> df.unstack()
7023         one  a  1.0
7024              b  2.0
7025         two  a  3.0
7026              b  4.0
7027         dtype: float64
7028         """
7029         from pandas.core.reshape.reshape import unstack
7030 
7031         return unstack(self, level, fill_value)
7032 
7033     _shared_docs[
7034         "melt"
7035     ] = """
7036     Unpivot a DataFrame from wide to long format, optionally leaving identifiers set.
7037 
7038     This function is useful to massage a DataFrame into a format where one
7039     or more columns are identifier variables (`id_vars`), while all other
7040     columns, considered measured variables (`value_vars`), are "unpivoted" to
7041     the row axis, leaving just two non-identifier columns, 'variable' and
7042     'value'.
7043     %(versionadded)s
7044     Parameters
7045     ----------
7046     id_vars : tuple, list, or ndarray, optional
7047         Column(s) to use as identifier variables.
7048     value_vars : tuple, list, or ndarray, optional
7049         Column(s) to unpivot. If not specified, uses all columns that
7050         are not set as `id_vars`.
7051     var_name : scalar
7052         Name to use for the 'variable' column. If None it uses
7053         ``frame.columns.name`` or 'variable'.
7054     value_name : scalar, default 'value'
7055         Name to use for the 'value' column.
7056     col_level : int or str, optional
7057         If columns are a MultiIndex then use this level to melt.
7058 
7059     Returns
7060     -------
7061     DataFrame
7062         Unpivoted DataFrame.
7063 
7064     See Also
7065     --------
7066     %(other)s : Identical method.
7067     pivot_table : Create a spreadsheet-style pivot table as a DataFrame.
7068     DataFrame.pivot : Return reshaped DataFrame organized
7069         by given index / column values.
7070     DataFrame.explode : Explode a DataFrame from list-like
7071             columns to long format.
7072 
7073     Examples
7074     --------
7075     >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'A': {0: 'a', 1: 'b', 2: 'c'},
7076     ...                    'B': {0: 1, 1: 3, 2: 5},
7077     ...                    'C': {0: 2, 1: 4, 2: 6}})
7078     >>> df
7079        A  B  C
7080     0  a  1  2
7081     1  b  3  4
7082     2  c  5  6
7083 
7084     >>> %(caller)sid_vars=['A'], value_vars=['B'])
7085        A variable  value
7086     0  a        B      1
7087     1  b        B      3
7088     2  c        B      5
7089 
7090     >>> %(caller)sid_vars=['A'], value_vars=['B', 'C'])
7091        A variable  value
7092     0  a        B      1
7093     1  b        B      3
7094     2  c        B      5
7095     3  a        C      2
7096     4  b        C      4
7097     5  c        C      6
7098 
7099     The names of 'variable' and 'value' columns can be customized:
7100 
7101     >>> %(caller)sid_vars=['A'], value_vars=['B'],
7102     ...         var_name='myVarname', value_name='myValname')
7103        A myVarname  myValname
7104     0  a         B          1
7105     1  b         B          3
7106     2  c         B          5
7107 
7108     If you have multi-index columns:
7109 
7110     >>> df.columns = [list('ABC'), list('DEF')]
7111     >>> df
7112        A  B  C
7113        D  E  F
7114     0  a  1  2
7115     1  b  3  4
7116     2  c  5  6
7117 
7118     >>> %(caller)scol_level=0, id_vars=['A'], value_vars=['B'])
7119        A variable  value
7120     0  a        B      1
7121     1  b        B      3
7122     2  c        B      5
7123 
7124     >>> %(caller)sid_vars=[('A', 'D')], value_vars=[('B', 'E')])
7125       (A, D) variable_0 variable_1  value
7126     0      a          B          E      1
7127     1      b          B          E      3
7128     2      c          B          E      5
7129     """
7130 
7131     @Appender(
7132         _shared_docs["melt"]
7133         % dict(
7134             caller="df.melt(",
7135             versionadded="\n    .. versionadded:: 0.20.0\n",
7136             other="melt",
7137         )
7138     )
7139     def melt(
7140         self,
7141         id_vars=None,
7142         value_vars=None,
7143         var_name=None,
7144         value_name="value",
7145         col_level=None,
7146     ) -> "DataFrame":
7147         from pandas.core.reshape.melt import melt
7148 
7149         return melt(
7150             self,
7151             id_vars=id_vars,
7152             value_vars=value_vars,
7153             var_name=var_name,
7154             value_name=value_name,
7155             col_level=col_level,
7156         )
